<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Ferriola     03-12 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Ferriola,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Chicago Crime Boss Dies After Heart Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Ferriola, the reputed chieftain of
organized crime in Chicago, died Saturday following his second heart
transplant in recent weeks. He was 61.
   Ferriola died at 2:50 a.m. in Methodist Hospital, where he was a
patient of well-known heart specialist Dr. Michael DeBakey, hospital
spokeswoman Cindy Lea said. She said she had no further information.
   Ferriola had undergone two heart transplants in the last few
weeks, Chicago television stations WLS and WBBM reported Saturday.
His body rejected the first heart and was rejecting the second when
he died, WLS said.
   Federal officials said Ferriola emerged as the head of organized
crime in Chicago in 1986, after prison sentences were handed to
long-time reputed boss Joseph ``Doves'' Aiuppa and No. 2 man John
``Jackey the Lackey'' Cerone.
   Aiuppa, 81, and Cerone, 74, received 28{-year prison terms for
skimming profits from Las Vegas gambling casinos.
   In the early 1970s, Ferriola served a federal prison term for
taking part in a multimillion-dollar nationwide gambling syndicate,
Healy said.
   Ferriola lived in a 14-room mansion in the wealthy western
Chicago suburb of Oak Brook, the Chicago Tribune said.
</TEXT>
