<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Paraguay     03-12 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Paraguay,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Paraguayan Interior Minister Seeks Refuge in Honduras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sabino Augusto Montanaro, the former
Paraguayan interior minister who sought political asylum after the
ouster of President Alfredo Stroessner, arrived in Honduras Saturday
.
   ``I will be permanently grateful to the government and the people
of Honduras,'' Montanaro told reporters at the Tegucigalpa
International Airport.
   Montanaro, 66, sought asylum in the Honduran Embassy in the
Paraguayan capital of Asuncion on Feb. 3 after Stroessner was forced
from office in a bloody coup.
   He left the embassy early Saturday, two days after the new
Paraguayan government granted him a safe-conduct pass to leave the
country.
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who led the coup against Stroessner,
dissolved Congress after being sworn in as president and has said
national elections will be held May 1.
   Gen. Stroessner, who ruled Paraguay for 34 years, fled to Brazil
where he is living in exile.
   There were reports that as many as 300 people were killed during
the coup but Rodriguez has said the casualties, including dead and
wounded, did not exceed 50.
   Montanaro's flight on the Brazilian airline Varig left Asuncion
Saturday after a two-hour delay blamed on a false bomb threat.
   He was accompanied by his wife, Martha, his children Augusto and
Silvia, and the Honduran ambassador to Paraguay Roberto Suazo Tome.
   The Honduran government of President Jose Azcona Hoyo made no
comment on Montanaro's arrival.
</TEXT>
