<FIRST>r a AM-EscapeeStandoff     03-12 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escapee Standoff,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Escapee Dies as Gunfight, Fire End 12-hour Standoff with Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An escaped prisoner took six people hostage and
held police at bay for 12 hours with an assault rifle, but died
early Saturday when a fire and gun battle ended the standoff,
officials said.
   Gomard Olayan, 30, released five of the hostages, including a
police officer, and the sixth escaped 10 minutes after a tear gas
cannister started a fire in a second-floor apartment in the Honolulu
suburb of Waipahu.
   Police said it was not immediately clear whether Olayan died in
the fire, during the gunfight or by his own hand. He was armed with
a Soviet-made AK-47 assault rifle, authorities said.
   Olayan fired at least seven bursts of three shots each during the
standoff, said Sgt. Mike Kaainoa. No one was injured by the bullets,
police said.
   The standoff came to a head at 9:25 a.m. with a rapid exchange of
gunfire between Olayan and police. Police then fired tear gas into
the apartment.
   Police decided to open fire because Olayan had been shooting
sporadically out of the apartment throughout the morning, said Maj.
Robert Au, head of the detective division.
   ``We were afraid that some of these shots might injure someone in
the community,'' Au said.
   Olayan and 26-year-old Roy Frisbee escaped from the Oahu
Community Correctional Cetner on Thursday night by taking two guards
hostage with a handgun. Frisbee remained at large Saturday, police
said.
   Both escapees were awaiting trial on numerous charges, including
the illegal possession of firearms and terroristic threatening,
police said.
   Police said Olayan took three children and an adult hostage
around 10 p.m. Friday night. Police said the adult hostage was
Dennis Busano, Olayan's friend and father of the children.
   At 12:15 a.m. Saturday, Olayan released the four hostages in
exchange for a police officer and a man identified by witnesses as
Jonathan Perez, 26.
   Olayan eventually allowed the officer to leave, according to
Roselyn Ginger Wilheln, Perez's girlfriend.
   Perez had a leg amputated last month after a gunshot wound became
infected, according to his girlfriend, Ms. Wilheln said. He was
taken from the apartment by police within 10 minutes of the start of
the fire.
   Police and firefighters found Olayan's body in the bathroom of
the apartment. They entered the apartment at 10:33 a.m., about an
hour after the fire broke out.
   A nursing supervisor at St. Francis Medical Center said Perez was
in good condition. She did not specify Perez's injuries. Police said
Perez was arrested, but did not say what charges he faced.
   Residents of the Nani Gardens apartment complex were evacuated
and spent the night huddled in blankets at a nearby shopping center.
</TEXT>
