<FIRST>r i BC-Israel-Lebanon     03-12 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Israel-Lebanon,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>2 Guerrillas Killed in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed two Arab guerrillas
early Sunday on the northern border of Israel's self-declared
security zone in southern Lebanon, the army said.
   No Israeli soldiers were hurt in the fighting, an army
announcement said.
   It was the third confrontation between Israeli soldiers and
guerrillas in south Lebanon since February 23. The two other
incidents were described by Israel as PLO attempts to carry out
attacks inside Israel and became an issue in the U.S. dialogue with
the PLO.
   An army announcement referred to the guerrillas as ``terrorists''
but did not indicate if they were Palestinian or Lebanese. A
spokeswoman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said she had no
information on whether the guerrillas were trying to infiltrate into
Israel.
   The confrontation in Lebanon took place near the town of Hasbaya,
about five miles north of the Israeli border, the army said.
   Hasbaya is within the security zone set up by Israel to protect
its northern border in 1985 when it withdrew the bulk of its forces
from Lebanon after a three-year occupation.
   Seven Palestinian guerrillas were killed in the two earlier
battles, and the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a
Marxist faction of the PLO, said they were members of their group.
   One confrontation took place on Feb. 23, and the second was on
March 2.
   Israel accused the Palestinian group of trying to infiltrate into
Israel in the two previous confrontation and called on the United
States to halt its dialogue with the PLO, saying PLO chief Yasser
Arafat had broken his pledge to stop terrorist attacks.
   U.S. officials criticized the PLO for the incidents, but it also
called for a halt to retaliatory Israeli bombing raids against
Palestinian positions in south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
