<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-OzoneProtest     03-12 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ozone Protest,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Trees Protest Outside Downing Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six protesters dressed as trees went to Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's residence Sunday to urge her government
to do more to protect the world's rain forests.
   The members of the United Nations Association Youth Council
delivered 22 chestnut saplings, one for each member of the Cabinet,
and a letter welcoming the government's recent support for saving
the ozone layer.
   ``We are glad the government is concerned about the ozone layer
but we want to see more action on the crucial environmental question
of the destruction of the rain forests,'' said the council's
chairman, David Kennedy.
   ``Saving the rain forests is as crucial as saving the ozone
layer.''
   Britain was the host of a 120-nation conference last week that
ended with industrialized nations reaffirming plans to ban by the
end of the century synthetic chemicals known as chlorofluorocarbons.
   The compounds destroy the ozone shield that protects the Earth
from the sun's cancer-causing ultraviolet rays.
</TEXT>
