<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Peacekeepers Arrive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 70 British troops arrived Sunday
to join the advance contingent of U.N. peacekeepers preparing to
monitor Namibia's transition to independence.
   The British unit brought its own four-wheel drive vehicles and
drove in convoy to its temporary quarters, a South African army base
south of Windhoek. Tents reserved for the Britons had no mattresses
on the beds, and South African officers began a search to find some.
   Soldiers and U.N. administrative personnel from Australia,
Canada, Denmark, Finland, Italy, Kenya, Poland, and Spain already
are in Namibia. Some 4,650 troops from more than 20 countries are to
arrive by the end of the month.
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia since World War I, is to
begin implementing independence next month, leading to elections in
early November.
   The South-West African People's Organization, which has waged a
guerrllia war against South African rule here for 23 years, is
favored to win most votes. It needs two-thirds of ballots to have
full control of a government.
