<FIRST>r i AM-Refusenik     03-12 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refusenik,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Refusenik Arrives in Israel after 18-Year Wait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the Soviet Union's longest-waiting
refuseniks, Yuli Kosharovsky, arrived in Israel to a festive welcome
Sunday after an 18-year struggle to gain his freedom.
   ``We welcome you with open arms and with a heart full of hope
that many, many of our brothers in the Soviet Union will come in
your footsteps,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said as he greeted
Kosharovsky at the airport.
   Choking back tears, the refusenik said in Hebrew: ``All my life,
my greatest ambition has been to be an Israeli.''
   He said more than half a million of the Soviet Union's 2.5
million Jews would prefer to leave.
   In February, 2,425 Jews left the Soviet Union, but only 13
percent went to Israel. Most chose the United States.
   Kosharovsky, 48, arrived in Israel with his wife Ina, 42, and
their three children.
   Kosharovsky was a leading Hebrew teacher in the Soviet Union and
was arrested six times for his Zionist activities.
   He first was refused an emigration visa in March 1971 and applied
22 times before he got permision to leave.
