<FIRST>u a AM-CaveWoman Bjt   03-12 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cave Woman, Bjt,0820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman in Isolation Experiment in Cave Lives Like Rat in a Cage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time passes slowly for Stefania Follini.
   The Italian woman has fallen into a routine of staying awake 23
hours, then sleeping for 10, after being holed up in a cave for two
months as part of a research project into the effects of isolation.
She has no sun, radios or clocks to guide her sense of time, and
little contact with other humans.
   ``Sunday, Feb. 12, 10 a.m.,'' Miss Follini writes on a computer
at a desk in her plastic habitat at one end of the cave.
   Actually, it's noon on Wednesday, March 8.
   On Jan. 13, the 27-year-old Miss Follini climbed 30 feet below
the earth's surface and into the 200-foot-long Lost Cave in the
hills west of Carlsbad to begin a four- to five-month isolation
experiment. An Italian research group is sponsoring the experiment,
along with various U.S. universities and the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration.
   As she moves about in her two-room, 200-square-foot Plexiglas
house, Miss Follini resembles a laboratory rat in a cage.
   Researchers monitor her with three video cameras and microphones,
and they type in occasional messages to her computer, but Miss
Follini cannot see or hear another human.
   During her waking hours, she sometimes taps away at her computer
like a subject in a B.F. Skinner experiment as researchers in a
trailer above record the results of tests of her concentration,
memory and reasoning ability.
   One thing researchers are discovering in isolation experiments _
intended, among other things, to give them insight into how humans
might react on interplanetary space flights _ is that men tend to be
more cheerful in long isolation than women.
   Maurizio Montalbini, the experiment coordinator who once spent
six months isolated in a cave, alludes to that in a brief computer
conversation in Italian with his fellow native of Ancona, Italy.
   ``You should change your sex,'' Montalbini writes to the
glum-looking Miss Follini. ``You always seem like a sad one.''
   ``I feel sadder some times than others,'' she replies.
   After chatting via computer for a little bit, Montalbini asks
Miss Follini to take the series of computerized mental tests, which
she performs about once a week. Miss Follini, who had been
interrupted from reading a novel to take the medical measurements
and relay them by computer, becomes a little sarcastic.
   ``Great idea, like a dessert!'' she responds.
   An interior decorator by profession, Miss Follini has livened up
her 10-by-10-foot living area with colorful figures cut out of
construction paper and glued to the walls. Among the paper
decorations: wine bottles, a flower box and a ``window,'' covered
with blue paper lace curtains, that looks out onto a white paper
moon and stars. A brown paper cat sits beside the windowsill.
   Miss Follini spends much of her time kneeling on a blue mat,
reading. She brought 400 books with her: novels, histories, English
primers. She stays in shape by practicing judo moves.
   She is remarkably quiet.
   Even though researchers can hear her, she prefers to communicate
with them by computer.
   She does talk a little to her pets _ two mice she dubbed Giuseppe
and Nicoleta, and a salamander _ all found in the cave. She keeps a
vigil to prevent the rodents from gnawing at cables or eating her
food, which consists mostly of rice and beans she cooks on an
electric stove.
   Long-term space flight might be a lot like this, except for the
lack of gravity in space.
   Medical researchers are especially interested in finding out what
isolation does to one's emotional and mental well-being.
   ``Stefania is fine,'' says Andrea Galvagno, an Italian doctor who
alternates 24-hour monitoring shifts with Montalbini. ``As of now,
she hasn't expressed any desire that deals with the outside world.''
   But it appears Miss Follini's world isn't quite a utopia. She
occasionally attaches electrodes to her head before she falls asleep
so researchers can study her brain waves in various stages of sleep,
and the results show symptoms of mild depression.
   Galvagno says he and Montalbini sometimes joke around with Miss
Follini to buoy her spirits.
   Montalbini says Miss Follini's ability to concentrate has
deteriorated. In previous experiments, people in isolation alone
have improved their concentration, while members of groups isolated
in caves have lost their concentration.
   About this time, around 4:30 p.m., Miss Follini walks over to her
computer, types in ``Ciaoooooooo,'' waves to the video camera, dims
the lights _ they always stay on _ lies on the mat under a blanket
and stares at the camera a while.
   Presently she closes her eyes and falls asleep: Stefania Follini,
a brown paper cat, two mice and a salamander.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890312-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-MeinKampf Bjt   03-12 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Mein Kampf, Bjt,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan to Publish `Mein Kamph' in Hebrew Stirs Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Holocaust survivor's Hebrew translation of
``Mein Kampf'' has touched off a controversy over whether the book,
which inspired the slaughter of 6 million Jews, should be published
in Israel.
   Author Dan Yaron argued Sunday that a Hebrew edition of the Adolf
Hitler's manifesto will educate young Israelis about the evils of
the Nazi regime. Other Holocaust survivors say it should never
appear on Israeli bookshelves.
   So far, Yaron has not found a publisher.
   ``It's not easy to get someone to publish a book that is
connected to Hitler,'' said Yaron, who spent the past 18 months
translating the first volume of ``Mein Kampf.''
   ``But 50 years after Hitler, we must be strong enough to look at
who he was,'' said Yaron, who fled his native Vienna in 1938 after
watching Nazi troops parade down the main street of the Austrian
capital.
   Yaron, a retired educator, said in an interview that young Jews
should read ``Mein Kampf'' as a warning against racist ideology. He
said, for example, that there were disturbing anti-Arab sentiments
expressed by extreme right Israeli politicians.
   ``The new generation needs ... to know about the dangers that can
occur,'' he said. ``There are (Israelis) who promote racism.''
   Yaron said the fact his parents were killed by the Nazis while
trying to escape from Austria has strengthened his determination to
see the book published in Israel.
   ``If people like my father ... would have had the internal
strength to read the book, they would have known, and things would
have ended differently,'' he said.
   Other Holocaust refugees vehemently disagree with Yaron, saying
publication would stir deep emotion in a nation that was founded in
part to shelter the survivors of the Nazi horrors.
   If it is published, ``there will be battles in the street,''
predicted Noah Klieger, a survivor of the Aushwitz concentration
camp, who covers Holocaust affairs for the daily Yediot Ahronot
newspaper.
   ``We need freedom of opinion, but there is a limit, and Hitler is
the limit,'' he said in an interview. ``The man who wrote this book
destroyed _ physically destroyed _ a third of the Jewish people.''
   Stefan Grayek, president of the World Federation of Jewish
Fighters, Partisans, and Camp Inmates, also opposes publication.
   ``Jews don't need to read about the worst anti-Semitism the world
has ever seen,'' he said. ``We don't need to revive Hitler,
certainly not in Israel, definitely not in Hebrew.''
   He said some Holocaust survivors were considering legal action to
stop publication. But he said the federation decided against doing
anything, believing there was no real interest in the book.
   If published, he said, ``I think ...the book will end up in a
warehouse and not people's bookshelves,'' Grayek said.
   The Yad Vashem national Holocaust memorial has refused a request
to publish the translation, a spokesman for Yad Vashem said.
   ``I question why anyone would publish the book,'' said spokesman
Menahem Fogel. ``It's going to upset a lot of people, and I can't
see it selling a lot of copies.''
   ``The book is available in its original language, and if
researchers want to gain access to the book it is best that they
study it in the original language,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
