<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MitchellAtTheHelm Bjt   03-12 0977</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mitchell At The Helm, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Majority Leader Prevailed in First Major Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Democratic Sen. Sam Nunn came under
Republican attack during the debate over John Tower's nomination as
defense secretary, Majority Leader George Mitchell stepped forward
to deflect the blows.
   And when the Republicans switched gears and insisted that the key
issue was President Bush's prerogative of picking his own Cabinet,
Mitchell deftly rebutted by cautioning against
``self-righteousness.''
   ``Don't get too locked into your present views,'' the Maine
senator said after reciting chapter and verse a series of past GOP
votes against high-level Democratic appointees. ``You may get into
another one in not too long.''
   If George Bush had much at stake in the Tower fight that
culminated with rejection of the nomination, so did George Mitchell,
a 55-year-old Maine native of Maine whose rise to the pinnacle of
power in the Senate has been extremely rapid by congressional
standards. A former federal judge who was appointed to office in
1980, he won an underdog's race for a six-year term in 1982 and
parlayed that into a landslide re-election in 1988.
   He presided over the Democratic campaign committee that helped
oust the Republican majority in 1986 and two years later he won a
three-way race to become majority leader. He has stressed
cooperation with Bush in the early months of his tenure, yet also
outlined a Democratic agenda that includes ethics legislation,
environmental concerns and social issues such as raising the minimum
wage.
   Still, a miscue could have marred his first appearance in a
leading role for a party trying to maintain its standing during
lengthy Republican control of the White House.
   Mitchell walked a narrow line. He stressed throughout the debate
that he meant no political injury to Bush. Yet he also was the
careful keeper of the vote count that sealed Tower's rejection.
   He put his low-key debating style on display for the first time
in contrast to veteran GOP leader Bob Dole's more aggressive
approach.
   Moreover, Mitchell apparently emerged without unduly antagonizing
senators on the other side of the aisle.
   Dole said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that the Senate
probably will be back to normal within a month or two despite
bruised feelings over the Tower episode.
   ``I think you can say that the nomination is gone but not
forgotten,'' said Dole. ``The memories will be around for a while.
There will be some bruised feelings. But I think in probably 30 to
60 days we'll be back to normal. The scars aren't that deep.''
   One Democratic committee chairman, speaking anonymously, said
Mitchell's approach was to avoid the appearance of partisanship, yet
at the same time to support Nunn and the Democrats on the Armed
Services Committee who recommended rejection of Tower's nomination.
   ``I thought he acted calm and cool throughout. He made nobody mad
on the Democratic side,'' said Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., one of
three Democrats to vote in favor of confirmation. ``He never did any
real what you call arm-twisting.''
   In the same vein, Mitchell minimized the importance of the Tower
debate to his own political fortunes even as he acknowledged
judgments ``inevitably'' would be made on how he performed.
   After initially remaining in the background, Mitchell assumed an
increasingly prominent role in the confirmation struggle.
   Mitchell learned Monday night that the votes were in hand to
defeat Tower's nomination, and let the Republicans know by telling
reporters on Tuesday.
   The following day _ Wednesday _ Democrat Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
became the third Democrat to announce his support of Tower. But then
a string of three wavering Democrats quickly came to the floor and
declared their opposition. The effect was to blunt the impact of
Bentsen's long-awaited decision and seal Tower's defeat. It all bore
the marks of skillful behind-the-scenes stage managing.
   Mitchell and Nunn worked closely and several Republicans said it
was the decision by the highly respected Nunn to oppose Tower that
made confirmation difficult to achieve.
   Yet when Nunn himself came under attack from Republicans for
detailing investigators from a subcommittee he heads to check out
allegations against Tower, Mitchell came to his defense.
   ``We are not going to get in a position here where one, two,
three, four, five, six, seven people come over here and ask the same
question and the senator (Nunn) has to give the same answer over
again,'' said Mitchell.
   And he showcased his debating skills when he replied to
persistent Repulican claims that Bush was entitled to have the
nomination confirmed as a matter of presidential prerogative.
   If they serve long enough, he said, all senators of both parties
``will inevitably contradict ourselves. We will meet ourselves
coming around the corner on some issue.''
   He cited Repulican opposition to several appointments made by
former President Carter a decade ago and said: ``There was no talk
then about the president having his own way. There was no talk then
about the president winning the last election. There was no talk
then about the future of the confirmation process. There was no talk
then about the fairness of the process.''
   Mitchell also worked to thwart Dole's more aggressive approach to
the debate and his efforts to shake loose a few extra votes by
accusing the Democrats of treating Tower unfairly.
   When Dole suggested that Tower be given the right to come to the
Senate and respond to allegations against him, Mitchell immediately
replied that he would be willing to give it serious consideration.
By not rejecting the proposal outright, several Democrats said, the
Maine senator denied Dole the right to level a fresh charge of
unfairness.
   And when Dole finally made a formal proposal on the Senate floor
_ after the outcome of the struggle was clear _ Mitchell blocked it
and the Republicans did not pursue it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
