<FIRST>r p AM-Nunn-Democrats     03-12 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nunn-Democrats,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>To Run or Not to Run? Nunn Maintains He's Not Interested</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spotlight of the John Tower controversy
proved hotter than Sam Nunn had anticipated and the Georgia senator
now yearns for a chance to lower his profile.
   ``I'd like to go down to Houston County and check titles on real
estate for about six months,'' Nunn told reporters at the annual
meeting of the Democratic Leadership Council.
   The reporters laughed and the senator smiled. But he looked like
a man who meant what he said.
   Like it or not, Nunn will have to reconcile himself to a
prominence most politicians would relish.
   For the first time in his public career, Nunn was the target of
partisan attacks from opponents who questioned his tactics and
motives as the leader of the opposition to the Tower nomination.
   It was a trial by fire that seems to have strengthened his
standing as a national figure. President Bush may not like the role
Nunn played in defeating his first choice to head the Pentagon, but
the president seemed as eager as Nunn to get the bitterness behind
him.
   Before the Tower debate, Nunn was seen as a figure apart from
politics. ``Respected'' was the word most often used to describe the
bespectacled Georgian who had carved out a reputation as the
Senate's foremost authority on defense issues.
   The past couple of years saw a shift in Nunn's approach. No
longer did he shy away from partisan jabs at the Republican
administration. He mulled a run for the 1988 Democratic presidential
nomination and campaigned extensively for Michael Dukakis in his
ill-fated effort to regain the presidency for the Democrats.
   But the Tower nomination was a much more dramatic step into the
thick of partisan politics. That battle over, the question he often
is asked is, what next?
   ``I have no plans or any inclination to run for president in
1992,'' he said. ``I'd like to have s much lower profile.''
   As chairman of the DLC, Nunn had the kind of forum he seems to
relish _ one that features an often dry discussions of issues.
   Without question, Nunn was the dominant figure at the two-day
meeting, despite the presence of three of the contenders for the
1988 Democratic presidential nomination _ Jesse Jackson, Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. of Tennessee and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri.
   ``When the history of the 101st Congress is written, it will be
about Sam Nunn,'' said Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of
Maine. ``He represents the best that our democratic society has to
offer.''
   Mitchell's tribute to Nunn was all the more striking for being
just one of many voiced during the conference.
   But while Nunn was bombarded with the sort of flattery that would
prompt most politicians to begin thinking about their Cabinet
choices, a bid for the presidency would make the fight over Tower
seem gentle.
   Nunn represents his party's most conservative wing.
   While he commands unquestioned respect on defense issues his
support for the Reagan economic program would and his conservative
positions on other domestic issues would raise bitter opposition
from the party activists who still control the presidential
nominating process.
   The ideological split in the Democratic Party was dramatized by
the presence at the DLC meeting of Jackson, who symbolizes an
approach the DLC was created to combat.
   ``Reverend Jackson is a very credible spokesman for his point of
view,'' said Nunn. ``Obviously, he and I have some very fundamental
differences in philosophy.''
   Those differences will not easily be bridged.
   -0-
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITORS NOTE: Donald M. Rothberg is chief political writer</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
