<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-12 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people think they have space problems when
the hall closet won't take one more winter coat or when there's no
more room in the attic for grandma's collection of National
Geographics.
   That's nothing.
   The Field Museum of Natural History is trying to cope with 2
million beetles, 9.6 million insect specimens, 1.7 million fish,
381,000 birds, 2.4 million plants, a half-million fossils, 600,000
artifacts _ 20 million specimens in all with 400,000 more coming in
each year.
   ``We're approaching a sort of gridlock,'' said the museum's
geology department chairman, John Bolt.
   The botany department bulges with twice as many plant specimens
as it was designed to hold. And the geology department is cramming
so many fossils into storage drawers that some may get damaged.
   The museum, which says its holdings are widely used by
researchers, is planning to close two courtyards inside the building
for construction of more storage, and is considering building four
underground, two-story vaults.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of the first St. Patrick's
Day parade here nine years ago weren't sure how popular it would be,
since South Dakota is populated mainly by descendants of
Scandinavians and Germans.
   But ``good Lord, they came out of the woodwork,'' says Bill
Reynolds, who helped plan event back in 1980. Organizers had figured
on maybe 20 parade entries. They got more than 350.
   Thousands of revelers are expected to converge on Sioux Falls
again Friday to celebrate what has become one of the city's most
popular holidays.
   Sylvia Henkin, chairwoman and owner of KSOO Radio Inc., was
instrumental in planning the first Sioux Falls parade.
   ``They called me the Jewish leprechaun,'' she recalls.
   She's not sure why the idea caught on, but she says the bitter
South Dakota winters may have had something to do with it.
   ``I think people sort of have cabin fever in this part of the
country after being winterized and locked up,'' she said. ``All you
need is a good excuse to celebrate and, my goodness, this is a good
excuse.''
   ``This thing has taken off by itself and mushroomed,'' Henkin
said. ``Really, the only thing we would need to do is blow a whistle
and it would take off by itself.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DUMAS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pauline Hobgood and Raymond Smith married
more than 60 years ago and were divorced a quarter-century ago.
Smith, 81, remarried once and Ms. Hobgood, 80, remarried twice.
   But they remained friends, and on Saturday they were married
again in a ceremony before dozens of relatives and friends in the
Dumas Nursing Center.
   ``They're making my brother and I very happy by remarrying,''
said Norma Jean Stewart, the couple's daughter. ``The family has
always hoped they would get back together.''
   The ring used in the wedding was the same one Smith gave to Ms.
Hobgood in 1928.
   ``After the divorce, Mother always wore the ring on her right
hand,'' Stewart said.
   Ms. Hobgood said she and Smith ``never lost touch with each
other. One time, I even kept his money for him while he was in the
hospital.''
   Several days before the wedding, residents and staff members gave
Ms. Hobgood a bridal shower. The male residents, not to be outdone,
treated Smith to a bachelor party.
</TEXT>
