<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MinimumWage     03-12 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Pushing For Increase Bigger Than Bush Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>By PAUL PAGE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats in Congress didn't wait long to call
President Bush on his promise to raise the minimum wage.
   Democrats who saw their attempt to raise the $3.35 an hour wage
floor founder last year have renewed it with greater resolve,
setting up an early confrontation with Bush on a domestic issue that
reaches deep into the wallets of millions of Americans.
   Bush insists he will veto what may become the first piece of
major legislation to reach his desk if it doesn't match his plan,
despite agreeing that the minimum should be raised for the first
time in eight years.
   ``$4.25, that's it,'' Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole told a
Senate committee earlier this month, drawing a line she says Bush
will not cross.
   But Democrats are putting their more ambitious increase on the
``fast track,'' using the minimum wage to take the lead on domestic
legislation after eight years of frustration under President Reagan.
   ``We're going to get this legislation achieved,'' said Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee. ``If it's the judgment that (Bush will) veto
it, we'll override it.''
   Quick action in the House and Senate _ and the concession by
Democrats that a sub-minimum wage they have long considered poison
could be part of a compromise _ has sparked hopes the minimum will
be raised for the first time since 1981.
   ``An increase in the minimum wage for the nation's lowest paid
employees is long overdue, and it is well past time for Congress to
act,'' Kennedy said earlier this month.
   Kennedy's committee recently passed his plan to raise the minimum
to $4.65 in three annual stages and a House subcommittee approved a
virtually identical plan on Thursday.
   The dollar difference is this: Democrats would take the minimum
to $3.85 an hour immediately and then add 40 cents a year for the
following two years. Bush would add 30 cents an hour annually for
three years.
   The main political battleground, however, is over Bush's desire
to add a second tier to leave the minimum at $3.35 an hour for the
first six months of employment for all newly hired workers. Bush
calls it a ``training wage,'' although opponents deride the term
because there are no requirements for any training.
   Kennedy, long opposed to a second scale, said last week he'd be
``glad to listen'' to a limited version.
   But he added, ``I'm not going to see the corruption of the
minimum wage by using the words `training wage' to throw older
workers out of work and displace those who want to work 40 hours a
week.''
   Rep. Austin Murphy, D-Pa., chairman of the House labor standards
subcommittee, said he was drawing up his own version of the reduced
wage as an alternative to the Republican plan and may introduce it
on the House floor. An aide said Murphy is looking at a duration of
30 to 90 days for a sub-minimum, and would likely tie it to a
percentage of the standard minimum.
   Labor Department figures show slightly fewer than 4 million
people work for the minimum wage, about 15 percent of them heads of
households. Some 11 million others earn less than $4.55 an hour,
according to a report on the raise that failed last year, and so
could see fatter paychecks if the minimum is boosted.
   The last time the rate was raised was in 1978, when it was
boosted in four stages that ended with the $3.35 an hour standard in
1981.
   ``Inflation has eroded the current minimum by 38 percent,''
Kennedy said. The administration's plan would eventually raise the
minimum by 26.8 percent while Democrats want a 39 percent hike.
   Bush puts the argument in terms of jobs, saying 650,000 people
would be thrown out of work if the minimum is raised to $4.65. Mrs.
Dole said the raise to $4.25 would cost 450,000 jobs, but other
provisions would make up part of that loss.
   However, Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the House
Education and Labor Committee, noted that since it was established
in 1938, ``each time the minimum wage increased, employment also
increased, with the two recession years the sole exception.''
   Frustrated by watching social programs suffer during Reagan's
administration, Democrats are keying their minimum wage plans to the
hope that Bush won't use his veto power.
   ``I take it seriously, but not very,'' Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, a member of the labor committee, said of the threat. ``I've
been around long enough to know that when a president threatens a
veto, sometimes it means he will veto and sometimes it means the
beginning of the negotiating process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
