<DOCNO> AP890312-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CatholicsTithing     03-12 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Catholics Tithing,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Official Says Flock Needs To Give More</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMITHFIELD, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Roman Catholic parishes may start a
pilot project to encourage ``sacrificial giving,'' similar to the
practice of tithing, because parishioners aren't giving enough to
allow church employees to get raises, a church official said.
   Bishop Louis E. Gelineau and the diocese's council of priests are
considering a proposal to encourage a ``sacrificial giving'' program
in four parishes that would be modeled on the tithing practice, said
the Rev. William J. McCaffrey, vicar for planning and finance of the
Diocese of Providence.
   The average parishioner puts roughly 1.1 percent of his or her
take-home pay in the collection plate, McCaffrey said Saturday at a
day-long conference for religious education teachers.
   As a result, the diocese has been unable to raise salaries for
parochial school teachers and other workers to keep up with public
school salaries in the past three years, he said.
   Some Protestant denominations practice tithing, which requires
congregants to give up to 10 percent of their incomes to the church.
</TEXT>
