<DOCNO> AP890312-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-BudgetTalks Bjt   03-12 0992</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget Talks, Bjt,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Where There's Smoke, There's Mirrors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All the budget talk now going on won't shrink
the deficit much unless White House and congressional leaders
conquer a pervasive feeling that it's politically best to let the
problem slide until next year.
   ``The smarter strategy would be to take the strong steps now,''
said Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee. ``But I'm not kidding myself. Right now the votes are not
there ... for that kind of package.''
   Fiscal policy experts agree it's better to reduce the deficit
while the economy is strong. Government statistics last week showed
unemployment at a 15-year low, and other signs are positive.
   A new round of negotiations on the fiscal 1990 budget, with White
House budget director Richard Darman, Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady and senior members of the House and Senate budget committees,
began Thursday and will resume Tuesday.
   ``There is still a great deal of hope and we're working
together,'' said Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, senior
Republican on the Senate Budget Committee.
   But the politicians have proven themselves unable to act without
some kind of calamity that creates public pressure, such as the 1987
stock market crash that forced a modest, two-year budget agreement
between President Reagan and Congress.
   No such crisis now exists.
   People ``don't see the greater evil lying out there from
inaction,'' said Robert Reischauer, director of the non-partisan
Congressional Budget Office. The budget negotiators ``don't have any
outside pressure either from the American people or the economy to
bolster up their backbone.''
   Reischauer, who became CBO director two weeks ago, agrees with
the many economists who believe the deficit probably won't cause an
immediately perceptible crisis as it gradually gnaws away at
America's economic strength.
   ``In an abstract sense, the vast majority of the American people
think something should be done,'' he said. But unless there's a
crisis such as a Wall Street crash or runaway inflation, ``they are
not willing to admit that they or their programs should be a part of
the solution.''
   ``There's a key element missing from the budget debate. And
that's a reason to act,'' said Stan Collender, a former staffer on
the House and Senate budget committees who now monitors federal
economic policy for the firm of Price Waterhouse.
   The Gramm-Rudman law was designed to create artificial crisis and
force action, using the threat of across-the-board spending cuts if
Congress and the president failed to meet pre-set deficit limits.
   But those ceilings depend on White House forecasts for the
economy and government spending. And, critics say, President Bush's
fiscal 1990 budget falls back on President Reagan's habit of
manipulating those forecasts to minimize tough budget choices.
   For example, Bush's plan to bail out the savings and loan
industry was created to be ``off-budget.'' Tens of billions of
dollars of costs thus do not show up on the balance sheets, and the
administration can claim it is meeting the Gramm-Rudman goal of a
deficit no larger than $100 billion in the new fiscal year.
   ``Spending saves money. Up is down. Black is white ... This is an
all-time low water mark in terms of kidding ourselves,'' said Carol
Cox, head of the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, who
also cited the Bush budget reliance on projections of sharply lower
interest rates _ at the same time rates are going up.
   With Bush unwilling to confront the deficit head-on, ``all of the
incentives are for Congress to buy additional smoke and mirrors'' to
avoid unpopular spending cuts or challenging Bush to a tax increase,
she said.
   ``I fearlessly predict the deficit next year won't be much lower
(than this year),'' she said.
   The deficit has actually gone up in the last two years despite
much-ballyhooed plans that were supposed to reduce it. The
government now expects red ink to exceed $170 billion this fiscal
year, although Gramm-Rudman called for $136 billion.
   Further hindering bold moves this year, especially from the
Democratic-controlled Congress, is political distrust.
   Darman told reporters last week he has assured Democrats the
White House would step forward and share blame for unpopular parts
in a budget package. But there is widespread doubt among the
opposition party that Bush would control such partisans as
Republican National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater and Ed Rollins,
who heads the House Republican campaign office.
   And Republicans in the Senate remember taking a gutsy stand to
reduce the deficit in 1985 with a plan that included cutting back
Social Security cost-of-living adjustments. Democrats hammered them
with that vote, and wrested away control of the Senate.
   ``I think after five years of almost continuous budget warfare
that has torn apart the Congress... this has become awfully
fruitless ground to plow,'' said Steve Bell, staff chief of the
Senate Budget Committee when the Republicans were in control.
   By relying on the rosy assumptions, Congress and the president
need to restrain spending growth or raise revenues by only about $13
billion out of a $1.16 trillion spending plan in order to avoid the
Gramm-Rudman automatic cuts.
   Bell, now with Salomon Brothers, predicts: ``A slide-through,
glide through budget resolution.''
   The participants in the talks won't say that themselves, but Sen.
Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, said
last week that Darman and the White House were privately seeking ``a
minimalist approach.'' Sasser also said that Darman said privately
that he might look at a tax increase next year.
   Darman denied it, but many on Capitol Hill say Bush's budget,
which carefully avoided spelling out billions of dollars in spending
cuts, made clear that the White House was no more willing to tackle
the deficit than Congress.
   ``We ought to get rid of this budget year as quickly as we can
because then, maybe next year, we can really get serious,'' said
Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., a member of the House Appropriations
Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
