<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-US Bjt   03-12 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-US, Bjt,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Paper Blames FBI For San Diego Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian newspaper Sunday blamed the FBI
for the bombing of a U.S. Navy captain's van and said Washington
tried to implicate Iran in the attack to justify deportation of
Iranian students.
   The English-language newspaper Kayhan International linked the
alleged U.S. plot to Western anger at Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
order that novelist Salman Rushdie be killed for his new novel,
``The Satanic Verses.''
   U.S. officials said Saturday the bombing of the van, driven by
the wife of the Navy man who mistakenly ordered the destruction of
an Iranian passenger jet, was being investigated as a possible
terrorist attack.
   The bombing ``will not be the last attempt to implicate Iran''
over the Rushdie controversy, Kayhan International said in an
editorial summarized by Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   The newspaper noted that one day before Friday's bombing in San
Diego, a U.S. Senate hearing was held at which an FBI official said
thousands of ``zealous'' Iranian students in the United States pose
a great threat to Americans.
   Therefore, the editorial said, Iran was not surprised when ``the
Federal Bureau of Investigation said that it was investigating
possible Iranian involvement'' in the bombing.
   In Washington, FBI spokeswoman Kathy Kennedy denied the
allegation and added, ``we have never made any linkage to Iran since
this incident happened.''
   ``We haven't gotten to the point (in the investigation) where we
could make such a linkage,'' she said.
   IRNA quoted the newspaper as saying the explosion was designed
``to create the necessary climate in the United States that would
justify the expulsion of Iranians.''
   No one was injured in the blast that destroyed a van driven by
Sharon Rogers, the wife of Navy Capt. Will Rogers III. Mrs. Rogers
got out of the van when she heard a noise witnesses described as
``two loud pops.'' The van exploded and burned moments later.
   As commander of the guided-missile cruiser USS Vincennes, Rogers
ordered the destruction of what he thought was an Iranian F-14 jet
fighter July 3 after the craft failed to respond to warnings in the
Persian Gulf.
   The aircraft was actually an Iranian civilian jet, and all 290
people aboard were killed.
   Rogers later said he acted to protect his ship and crew. He was
backed by the Reagan administration, which also decided to
compensate the victims' families.
   Iran's Parliament speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, has alleged that
Western governments may carry out terrorist attacks and link them to
Iran in retaliation for Khomeini's death order against Rushdie,
which was issued Feb. 14.
   Many Moslems believe ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam, and
Iranian clerymen have put a $5.2 million bounty on Rushdie's head.
The author, a British citizen who was born into a Moslem family, has
been in hiding since Feb. 14.
   At Thursday's hearing in Washington, an FBI official said about
15,000 ``zealous'' Iranian students are in the United States and
might try to seek revenge against Rushdie supporters.
   Oliver ``Buck'' Revell told a Senate subcommittee looking into
the impact of Khomeini's death order that the students are
particularly dangerous because they cannot be monitored and because
the State Department's standards for issuing visas are lax.
   
   The controversy over the death sentence led Iran to break
diplomatic ties with Britain on Tuesday. Britain in turn announced
it was expelling up to 30 Iranians.
   IRNA quoted Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashami as also
calling for an economic embargo of British goods.
   ``If we boycott Britain economically, we will strike the heaviest
blow on this old colonialist country and supporter of infidelity,''
he said Sunday.
</TEXT>
