<FIRST>r w AM-Kidrock     03-12 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidrock,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rory Zuckerman Playing To Growing Audiences Of Youngsters, Parents</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She once sang of broken hearts and lonely
nights to boozy lounge lizards, but Rory Zuckerman's singing career
really took off when she switched to children and the joys of eating
broccoli or splashing in a bubble bath.
   Known simply as Rory _ ``Zuckerman is too much of a mouthful for
kids,'' she says _ the 33-year-old mother from suburban Bethesda,
Md., is playing to growing audiences of youngsters and their parents
with her toe-tapping, finger-snapping tunes and gentle ballads, many
inspired by her sons Daniel, 5, and Max, 16 months.
   She and guitarist-arranger Tom Guernsey have produced their first
album, ``I'm Just a Kid!,'' containing 10 songs that blend jazz,
blues, Broadway show tunes, Motown, pop and 50s doo-wop in a musical
style that Rory calls ``kidrock.''
   Sales figures since the album was released last August on her
Roar Music label suggest that it's a big hit among kids caught in
the musical no man's land between cutesy nursery rhymes and MTV's
teen-oriented heavy metal. Their baby-boomer parents seem to like
it, too.
   Her national distributor, Alcazar Productions of Waterbury, Vt.,
says more than 3,000 albums were sold in the first three months,
already the fastest-selling debut by a children's singer. Sales,
mostly in book and toy stores, could top 200,000 in the first year.
   Rory's concert dates have taken her from Vermont to Little Rock,
Ark., and they're accelerating. She expects eventually to perform 50
to 75 out-of-town engagements annually.
   She and Guernsey just completed their second children's album and
will start work soon on a third. They're making plans to produce a
full-length music video. Rory has appeared on NBC-TV's ``Today'' and
several other network shows, and is a regular guest on radio talk
shows.
   It's all a far cry from the seven years when Rory sang Top 40
hits at nightclubs, shopping malls, high school proms and and motel
lounges, and recorded radio jingles for fast-food restaurants and
local auto dealerships.
   She played in some real dives, she recalls. Like bowling banquets
in American Legion halls and ``joints where bouncers had to take
customers outside,'' she said. Once, she dutifully sang requests all
evening for a drunk who threw up on her before he passed out.
   Worse, her career was going nowhere fast.
   After her marriage to Washington builder Shelton Zuckerman in
1981 and the birth of Daniel, Rory listened to children's music for
hours.
   ``I heard a lot of nice sounds, a lot of folk and nursery rhymes,
but nothing that was terribly creative,'' she said in an interview
between studio recording sessions.
   ``A lot of people assume that kids' music should be very quiet
and very sweet and dull,'' she said. But she learned from Daniel
that ``kids are much more sophisticated that we give them credit
for. And they can pick up the lyrics and rhythm of a song much
faster than adults do.''
   Rory and Guernsey, who has teen-age children and also was reared
on the 60s sounds of the Beatles, the Beach Boys and the Doobie
Brothers, started composing their own stuff about two years ago to
try to fill the gap.
   The infectious rub-a-dub rhythm of ``Bubble Bath'' is a favorite
of her toddler Max. The Incredible Piglets, stage puppets created by
a Jim Hensen designer, echo Motown's Supremes as they extoll the
delights of broccoli, squash and even rutabaga. ``Eating veggies is
our thing,'' they squeal.
   From a clash between Rory and Daniel, stuck at home and bored on
a rainy afternoon, came the lyrics to another song (``You, you're
drivin' me crazy, even though I'm crazy for you'') that examines
family frictions through the eyes of both parent and child.
   She and Guernsey aren't preachy moralists, Rory said, but if they
have a message it's to urge parents to ``lighten up and not take
everything so seriously.''
   ``Quit putting flash cards in the crib, quit pushing your kids to
be rocket scientists at age 3,'' she said. ``Let them have fun and
be innocent as long as they can, and don't forget to be a kid when
you're an adult.''
</TEXT>
