<FIRST>r w AM-GovernmentbyCommission     03-12 1022</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Government by Commission,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>It Often Produces More Rhetoric Than Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nine-member congressional commission recently
recommended a 50 percent pay raises for judges, government officials
and lawmakers. Nobody got a penny of it.
   A 14-member commission created by Congress labored for a year on
ways to reduce the federal deficit. It ended hopelessly deadlocked.
   Now an eight-member commission appointed by President Bush to
come up with ethical standards applying equally to all three
branches of government has reported that it can't be done.
   The ethics panel report released Friday is one more bit of
evidence that sometimes the commissions government creates to help
with its problems produce more rhetoric than results.
   ``As a mayor or a governor or a president or a legislative body
that is being criticized for something looks for something to do,
one of the easiest things to do is to study the matter, to create a
commission,'' said Donald Rumsfeld, a former secretary of defense
and a member of the deficit reduction panel.
   ``Some serve a useful purpose, some don't,'' he added.
   As Rumsfeld noted, Washington has no monopoly on the idea of a
study panel.
   Joe Pisciotte, a professor of government at Wichita State
University in Kansas, studied commissions created by the city of
Wichita.
   ``The term I would use for some of them is the politics of
avoidance, that if the governing body doesn't want to deal with a
particularly sensitive problem itself, it will create a board or
commission or task force and pass the heat, so to speak,'' Pisciotte
said.
   Although Pisciotte studied the phenomenon in his own back yard,
he thinks his conclusions also would apply to many federal
commissions.
   ``I think the pay commission was a prime example that was too
politically sensitive, too politically difficult ... so the people
who were ultimately responsible for that passed the heat,'' he said.
   As to why some commissions produce more results than others,
experts say there is no single answer.
   One of the most successful commissions in recent years was the
15-member National Commission on Social Security Reform, created by
President Reagan in 1981, which prepared the blueprint for a Social
Security rescue bill that barreled through Congress in a matter of
weeks.
   Contrasting this with the National Economic Commission that made
the deficit study, Rumsfeld said: ``The difference was that the
environment for a compromise solution on Social Security was
hospitable. They really felt that they needed some mechanism to come
together with a compromise package.''
   The National Economic Commission, on the other hand, was created
by Congress in the wake of the October 1987 stock market crash amid
considerable speculation that it would recommend some kind of tax
increase. By the time it wound up its work, the market had rebounded
and George Bush, who had criticized the panel during the campaign
and vowed to continue Reagan's opposition to any tax hike, was
president.
   ``The only reason that thing was appointed was that you had
President Reagan, who talked a great game and did some wonderful
things for the country, but added a trillion dollars of debt because
he basically was a compromiser and he didn't want to use the veto,''
said one Republican who has served on a number of government
commissions. He spoke on the understanding his name not be used.
   Kenneth Janda, a professor of political science at Northwestern
University, said he believes a legal requirement that the
commission's meetings be public added to its difficulties.
   ``To the extent that partisanship is a major variable, I think
that open hearings become a real problem, because if you make any
kind of tactical concession it can be interpreted by your rivals
within the party as giving away something,'' Janda said.
   However, William Agee of Boise, Idaho, president of the giant
Morrison-Knudsen heavy construction firm, who served on the equally
politically charged and equally open pay commission, said, ``I
personally believe that open meetings are OK. I think they serve a
useful purpose.''
   The Commission on Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries,
which came up with the 50 percent pay hike that lawmakers turned
down in the face of a public uproar, was created by Congress in
1967. It is commonly called the quadrennial commission because it
makes its recommendations every four years.
   In 1981, the commission recommended a 22 percent pay hike and
outgoing President Carter approved it. Reagan had given his
unofficial approval before taking office, but later changed his mind
and withdrew his OK. In 1985, the commission's recommendations did
result in a raise, bringing congressional salaries to $75,100 a year.
   Members of the current commission still defend their
recommendations, although Preston R. Tisch, a former postmaster
general, conceded that ``maybe the 50 percent was a little high.''
   ``We thought the administration was going to massage it a little,
which they didn't,`` Tisch said. ``That was a calculation on our
part.''
   Under the law, the president can disapprove a recommended
increase or approve it either in whole or in part. Reagan, still in
office when the commission made its report, approved it in full.
   The ethics panel was launched by Bush in January with
instructions to come up with standards ``equitable across all three
branches of the federal government.''
   It decided, however, that the basic law that prevents executive
officials from taking government actions affecting their financial
interests could not be applied to members of Congress for
constitutional and other reasons.
   In addition, it was unable to decide what categories of work
should be exempt from limits on outside earnings. So the panel
recommended that such determinations be left up to the president.
Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., chief architect of an ethics bill vetoed
by Reagan last year, denounced this as ``just a terrible idea.''
   R. James Woolsey, former counsel of the Senate Armed Services
Committee and a member of the ethics panel, said, ``The current
commission had to work very quickly because we were asked to get the
job done essentially in a month, and I think given that deadline,
did a rather strikingly complete job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
