<DOCNO> AP890312-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseManagement     03-12 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Management,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Study Finds Financial Management Reforms Inadequate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's implementation of financial
management reforms called for in a two-year law reorganizing the
Defense Department has been inadequate, according to a report
released Sunday.
   The General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm, found
that although the Army has consolidated its financial management
structure, the Navy has made few changes and the Air Force violated
the law.
   The Goldwater-Nichols Department of Defense Reorganization Act of
1986 required that the military departments designate a single
office within their civilian secretariats to conduct financial
management, which includes budgeting, accounting, cash management,
financial reporting, internal control and review.
   ``Offices within the military department secretariats and
military headquarters that parallel or duplicate these functions are
to be merged into a solitary office located within the civilian
secretariat,'' said Rep. J. Larry Hopkins of Kentucky, ranking
Republican on the House Armed Services investigations subcommittee.
   The GAO study determined whether the departments' reorganizations
satisfied the law and what effects the streamlining had on civilian
control.
   ``Although the Army has met the law's requirements, questions
over Navy compliance remain, and the Air Force, though complying in
principle, violated the spirit of the law,'' said Rep. Nicholas
Mavroules, D-Mass., chairman of the House subcommittee.
   The Army, according to the report, merged the office of the
comptroller into the office of the assistant secretary for financial
management. The authority of the civilian assistant secretary was
enhanced and the staff increased from 29 to about 220.
   The GAO found significant reliance on ``dual-hatting'' in the
Navy and also discovered that the Marine Corps Fiscal Management
Division handled financial management. The division reports to the
commandant, thus violating the law's requirment that financial
management be handled by a civilian secretariat.
   At the Air Force, the responsibility of financial management was
consolidated within the secretariat but at the same time the
position of civilian assistant secretary was eliminated and the job
of military comptroller was established. The comptroller was then
transferred from the secretariat to the Air Staff.
   ``The Air Force turned the law on its head,'' Hopkins said.
``Instead of strengthening civilian control, it bent the law by
giving authority for financial management to a three-star general.''
   The Defense Department, in response to the report, noted that the
secretary of the Air Force has more direct control over financial
management than ever before.
   The reorganization act was named after its chief sponsors, former
Sen. Barry Goldwater, R-Ariz., and the late Rep. Bill Nichols, D-Ala.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890312-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DeathPenalty     03-12 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Death Penalty,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Cuomo's Stance, New York May Be On Verge Of A Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state introduced the electric chair
to the world in 1890 and may be on the verge of commemorating the
centennial by putting it back into use after more than 25 years
without legal executions.
   ``Even the White House is interested,'' said state Sen. Dale
Volker, an upstate Republican who is chief sponsor of New York's
death penalty legislation in the Senate.
   Last week, after more than five hours of emotional debate, the
Democrat-controlled Assembly approved a death penalty bill, 97-48.
Of the five legislators who did not vote, two have voted for the
death penalty in the past and the other three have voted against it.
   That means the 150-member Assembly is within one vote of being
able to override a certain veto by Gov. Mario Cuomo, which requires
a two-thirds vote in each house _ that is, 100 votes in the Assembly.
   ``I think one of them will blink,'' predicted Vincent Graber,
chief sponsor of the bill in the Assembly, of the 51 opponents.
   The Republican-controlled state Senate has voted to override
Cuomo's vetoes of the death penalty since 1985 and is expected to do
so again this year.
   Cuomo, whose vetoes have stood for each of the past six years,
has vowed to ``make my case over and over again'' against the death
penalty in the next few months. Before Cuomo, Democratic Gov. Hugh
Carey delivered six years of vetoes.
   But Cuomo acknowledged: ``it's a difficult message. People are
angry and disgusted.''
   The violence brought by New York City's crack epidemic has
greatly increased public outcry for a death penalty in the state,
the nation's largest without capital punishment on the books.
   There were 1,586 murders in the city last year through Oct. 31,
compared with 1,691 in all of 1987. Statewide, Graber said during
the Assembly debate, there were 2,225 murders last year, up more
than 10 percent from 1987.
   Two weeks ago, a federal drug agent was gunned down in New York
City.
   And three men are on trial for the murder last year of Police
Officer Edward Byrne, who was guarding the house of a witness in a
drug case. Prosecutors say the hit was ordered by a jailed drug
kingpin.
   During last year's presidential campaign, Byrne's father gave his
son's badge to pro-death penalty Republican George Bush.
   Such carnage, plus a poll showing 73 percent of his constituents
favored the death penalty, prompted one long-time Assembly opponent,
Edward Abramson, to switch his vote last week. His represents a
district in Queens, the New York City borough where Byrne was killed.
   New York is one of 13 states without an operative death penalty
statute. Of the 37 with death penalty laws, only 13 have held
executions since the U.S. Supreme Court cleared the way for them to
resume in 1976; most of the others may have death sentences pending
on appeal.
   The bill being considered in New York would allow the death
penalty to be used against several types of murderers, including
contract killers and those who murder a police officer.
   New York's electric chair was last used on Aug. 15, 1963, when
Eddie Lee Mays, convicted of a 1961 bar shooting, became the 695th
person to die in it.
   Volker said he's been getting calls from all over the nation
about the New York situation. He said the White House asked the
state Senate's Washington office for information about the Assembly
vote.
   Legislators say they can already feel pressure building.
   ``I've already gotten calls from two police officers and a
detective,'' Assemblyman Vito Lopez, a Brooklyn Democrat who opposes
the death penalty, said the day after last week's vote.
   ``The next few weeks will be very rough,'' said Lopez. ``People
have talked about this being the time to take a vacation or move
away.''
   Lopez said he expects to vote again against the death penalty,
but he doesn't flatly rule out a change of heart.
   ``If my district substantially lobbied me (in favor of the death
penalty bill), ... then I would have to look at it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
