<DOCNO> AP890312-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-Meningitis     03-12 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Meningitis,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Outbreak Reported, 90 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new outbreak of meningitis has been
reported in northwestern Nigeria and has killed at least 90 people,
Radio Nigeria reported Sunday.
   The News Agency of Nigeria said an outbreak in late February
claimed 500 lives in eastern Anambra state, and epidemics in the
central states of Kwara and Niger resulted in a total of 143 deaths.
   The broadcast, monitored in Abidjan, said the latest outbreak was
centered in the Yauri district of Sokoto state and 400 people had
been hospitalized.
   The radio did not say when the latest outbreak began. They
identified the disease as cerebrospinal meningitis, and health
officials were quoted as saying a vaccination program was launched.
   Meningitis can be caused by bacterial or virus infection and
there are many strains.
</TEXT>
