<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     03-12 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians and Druse Battle; Beirut Airport Shut Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian army troops and Syrian-backed
Druse militiamen battled fiercely Sunday in hills above Beirut, a
day after authorities shut down Lebanon's only international airport.
   A police spokesman said the clashes erupted in the evening in and
around the strategic hilltop town of Souk El-Gharb. The violence
broke a cease-fire called at midnight Saturday to halt the worst
fighting around the capital in two years.
   There was no immediate word on casualties from Sunday's artillery
and rocket duels between Christian units and militiamen of Druse
warlord Walid Jumblatt.
   Six people have been killed and 32 wounded since clashes broke
out Wednesday.
   On Saturday, after Druse militiamen shelled the city's port and
the Defense Ministry compound, the Christian Cabinet ordered
Beirut's airport closed, saying it was unsafe.
   The order came as a rebuff to Jumblatt, the public works and
tourism minister in the rival Moslem Cabinet. He had vowed to keep
the airport operating.
   In retaliation, the Moslem Cabinet moved Sunday to block sea
traffic to Christian-controlled harbors.
   ``Because of escalating hostilities, maritime traffic to the
Beirut port and the port of Jounieh is henceforth declared unsafe,''
said a statement issued by the Moslem administration.
   There was no immediate indication of what measures were planned
to blockade the ports. The Moslems have no naval force but could
launch long-range artillery attacks on Jounieh, which is 12 miles
north of Beirut and the main port in the Christian heartland.
   Directors of Middle East Airlines, the state carrier, suspended
flights indefinitely after a five-hour meeting Sunday at the Beirut
airport.
   Hundreds of mostly Lebanese passengers crowded the airport
departure lounge, then returned to the city when the suspension was
announced.
   An airport official who requested anonymity said staff were still
reporting for duty because they did not know how long the airport
would be closed. ``It's a day-by-day affair,'' he said.
   Bulgaria's Balkan Airlines canceled its scheduled flight to
Beirut, the only regular Sunday international flight to the city,
the official said.
   Syrian, Soviet and Czechoslovakian carriers are the only other
foreign airlines that regularly use the airport.
   Most of Sunday's fighting focused on Souk El-Gharb, a mountain
peak 15 miles southeast of Beirut that commands a network of roads
leading from Druse-held territory to Lebanon's Christian section.
   Police said thousands of people huddled in basements and bomb
shelters all Saturday night as the battling troops shelled Beirut
suburbs and 21 residential districts on both sides of the front
lines in Lebanon's central mountain range. The fighting has
imperiled efforts by an Arab League foreign ministers' committee to
resolve a crisis that threatens the country with permanent partition
into sectarian cantons.
   The crisis erupted when President Amin Gemayel's six-year term
expired Sept. 22 and Parliament was unable to elect a successor.
   Gemayel named the army chief, Gen. Michel Aoun, a Maronite
Catholic, to lead an interim military Cabinet. Moslems and leftists
rejected the appointment and pledged allegiance to Salim Hoss, a
Sunni Moslem who governed under Gemayel.
</TEXT>
