<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Attitudes     03-12 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Attitudes,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adjustment Will Be Worse For Non-Union Eastern Workers _ Psychologists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern Airlines employees have the
psychological benefit of venting their feeling while picketing, but
non-union workers who found themselves out of work overnight will
have a tougher time adjusting, psychologists say.
   Mitchell Lee Marks, an organizational psychologist who helps
major companies through mergers and cutbacks, said he has been
impressed by the commitment of Eastern's unions to the 60-year-old
carrier.
   ``Eastern means something to them,'' said Marks, a consultant in
the Los Angeles office of Mercer Meidinger Hansen. ``I am impressed
by the extent in which people want to buy into their company
psychologically.''
   The union's tactic of focusing attention on Frank Lorenzo,
chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., as the bad guy in the
strike that virtually grounded the Miami-based airline is beneficial
for the employees, he said.
   ``What's fascinating about this case is it really comes down (to)
a personality battle. You don't hear people talking about the
economics of the situation,'' he said. ``That's part of the reason
they're rebelling against Lorenzo and not Eastern. It's this raider
Lorenzo who would come in and try to break them.''
   But all Eastern employees must face the changes that in less than
a week landed the nation's seventh-largest airline in bankruptcy
court.
   ``You lose all sense of control,'' said Robert Ziller, a
University of Florida psychology professor. ``But in a way they're
sustained by the fact they have a common opponent (Lorenzo). People
have been known to endure five years of bombing under those
circumstances.''
   Since many Eastern employees have long service with the carrier,
``they have to make almost a midlife, midcareer transition, which is
very, very difficult,'' said Douglas M. McCabe, an associate
professor of labor relations at the Georgetown University school of
business.
   An employee's standard of living ``gets cut drastically and
they're eating hot dogs. ... You're going from a very high standard
of living to one that's very low,'' he said.
   About 9,500 of the company's non-union workers ended up in the
worst psychological position of all when they were laid off without
notice last week, but some experts believe they will have an easier
time finding work because they have more flexible skills than the
pilots, machinists and flight attendants trained for a single job.
   Marks suggested group discussion sessions for non-union workers
to vent their feelings, an avenue union members have at the union
hall and on picket lines.
   Eastern workers will go through stages of denial, expecting the
strike to be over soon, to anger against Lorenzo and the strikers,
to planning strategy about staying with Eastern and job hunting, to
``acceptance, and you've got to go through those stages,'' Marks
said.
   McCabe expects a transition time of six months to a year while
people find new jobs.
   He and Marks likened the strike to recent mergers and corporate
cutbacks because of the similar labor adjustments.
   ``If you have a massive downsizing, you're truly changing the
organization. It cannot not change,'' said Marks, who acted as a
consultant as Delta Air Lines absorbed Western Airlines in 1987 and
helped with the creation of the Unisys corporation.
   ``There's a myth that some managers hold (that) the people will
be grateful that they survived,'' he said. ``But that's the farthest
from the truth because ... they're waiting for the other shoe to
drop.''
   Marks believes corporations have responsibility to help their
employees to adjust and employees need to take greater control of
their lives.
   ``The lesson to be learned for all employees is you've got to be
more responsible, to be more alert to what changes will come down
the pike,'' he said. ``The lesson to be learned by employers is to
send a message that their people matter.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
