<FIRST>r i AM-Botha     03-12 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says He Is Healthy Again, Hopes To Quell Power Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha denied
Sunday that he is involved in a power struggle with his heir
apparent, and he said he is ready to resume work following a stroke.
   In his first televised remarks since his Jan. 18 stroke, the
73-year-old Afrikaner said he has a constitutional duty to continue
in office.
   He made no reference to calls for him to step down when he spoke
in a 15-minute, prerecorded interview on state television network's
evening news show.
   Two weeks after his Jan. 18 stroke, Botha resigned as leader of
the National Party and was succeeded by Education Minister F.W. de
Klerk, 52.
   De Klerk and other senior Nationalist leaders met Botha last week
amid reports a solid majority of the party's parliamentary caucus
wants Botha to retire promptly or cede a significant share of power
to de Klerk. More talks are expected this week.
   Botha, who showed no signs of ill-health during the interview,
said de Klerk ``was being misused by some people,'' but insisted
there is no personal conflict.
   ``That would be a terrible charge against he and I,'' said Botha,
noting he appointed de Klerk to key parliamentary posts in past
years.
   ``Why? Because I have faith in him,'' Botha said.
   He indicated he was displeased with suggestions a de Klerk
presidency would herald a new era of political reform.
   ``I originated the concept of reform,'' Botha said.
   ``Mr. de Klerk has always shared these sentiments with me,'' he
added. ``There are forces in this country seeking to exploit an
unfortunate situation to sow political confusion.''
   Botha said even before his stroke, he advocated steps to lighten
the presidential workload. But he gave no hint when he might retire
from the post he has held since 1978. He said it was too early to
say when he might call a general election, which must be held within
12 months.
   ``I am healthy now,'' Botha said. ``I want to talk to fellow
Cabinet members. I want to talk to leaders of other population
groups on South Africa's future.''
   ``I'm not looking for power for the sake of power ... I'm open to
advice,'' he said.
   Near the end of his interview, he summed up his basic message:
``Stay calm _we're living in dangerous times, in difficult times.''
   The Botha-de Klerk confrontation was front-page news in all major
newspapers Sunday.
   ``Botha the Defiant,'' said a banner headline in the Sunday
Times, the country's largest-selling newspaper.
   ``P.W. Stands Alone,'' said the Sunday Star.
   ``Mr. Botha's attitude is quite irrational,'' said a Star
editorial. ``The real interests of this country ... are certainly
more crucial than the quirks of a fading strong man reluctant to let
go of power.''
</TEXT>
