<FIRST>r a AM-NoApples     03-12 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-No Apples,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>LA Schools Fear Apple A Day May Not Be Best Medicine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cafeterias at the nation's second-largest
school district will stop serving apples to students this week in
response to a report finding a cancer risk to children from a
chemical residue on some fruit.
   The ban also includes any apple products, including juice, pies
and applesauce, said Los Angeles Unified School District officials.
   The district's 592,000 students have eaten more than 5 million
apples each year, second only to the New York City school system,
where students consumed 13 million apples. New York schools enacted
a similar ban last week.
   ``That's a lot of apples, so we decided to do it in order to
protect the health and safety of students,'' said Los Angeles
district spokeswoman Eva Hain.
   The bans in Los Angeles and New York followed a Feb. 28 report by
the Washington-based National Resources Defense Council, which said
the chemical daminozide could increase the incidence of cancer in
children.
   Daminozide, sold under the brand name Alar, is sprayed on apple
trees in the spring and acts to keep apples on the tree longer. That
makes harvesting easier, improves the apples' color and firmness,
and extends their shelf life.
   Alar permeates the fruit's skin and cannot be peeled off or
washed away.
   Apple growers have criticized the report, contending that only 4
percent of the apples sold in the United States show any traces of
Alar and that those traces fall well below federal Environmental
Protection Agency levels.
   ``It's very disturbing that Los Angeles would arbitrarily make a
decision to ban apples based on the results of one report in which
the facts are not right,'' said Derl I. Derr, president of the
Virginia-based International Apple Institute, a trade organization
for the $1.2 billion-a-year industry.
   ``An apple a day is still healthy advice,'' Derr said.
   The federal EPA has moved to ban Alar eventually, but has said it
disagrees with the environmental group's contention that the risk
from using it is so great that an immediate ban is needed.
   The California Department of Food and Agriculture also criticized
the group's study.
   The Los Angeles school district will not serve apples or apple
products until it conducts its own laboratory tests, said Randy
Altenberg, deputy director of food services for the district.
   ``We are taking a cautious approach to a problem that could
affect the health of our schoolchildren,'' he said.
</TEXT>
