<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hot Day On Plains, Snow In Northeast, Rain In Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably warm weather covered much of the central part of the
nation Sunday and highs reached record levels in some spots, but
snow was scattered in the Northeast and part of the northern Plains.
   The unexpected warmth extended over the lower Mississippi Valley
and the lower two-thirds of the Plains.
   Early record highs included 60 at Casper, Wyo.; 92 at Lubbock,
Texas; and 93 at Midland, Texas.
   Snow fell during the afternoon from southern Maine to northern
sections of Rhode Island and Connecticut, and from east-central
through northwestern New York state.
   Snow also fell from south-central Minnesota across east-central
North Dakota.
   Rain fell along the southern coast of New England and also was
scattered over the northern half of the Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 18
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 95 at Childress, Texas.
Sunday's low for the Lower 48 states was 5 degrees above zero at
Sault Ste. Marie.
   For Monday, showers were forecast from the northern Pacific Coast
across western Montana.
   High in the 30s and 40s were predicted from New England across
Virginia, the Great Lakes, Minnesota, North Dakota, and from Montana
across northern Washington; in the 50s and 60s in North Carolina,
the Ohio Valley, the central Mississippi Valley, the remainder of
the northern two-thirds of the Plains, the Rockies, and the Pacific
Coast from central California through central Washington; near 90
from western Texas across the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and
80s in most of the rest of the nation.
