<FIRST>r p AM-Koch-Popularity     03-12 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koch-Popularity,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Koch Popularity Hits New Low, Giuliani in Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch, his popularity at a new
low, would lose at every level of a mayoral election, and former
U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani would win, according to a poll
released Sunday.
   Among Democrats, Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins would
beat Koch in a primary if it were being held now, according to the
poll. The primary is set for September and the general election for
November.
   The telephone poll, conducted March 3-7 by the Gallup
Organization for New York Newsday, surveyed 1,012 New Yorkers.
   Six months before the primary, 50 percent of those polled
disapproved of how the three-term mayor does his job, up five points
in three months. Thirty-one percent approved of the mayor's
performance, down from 37 percent in December.
   Sunday's poll showed Dinkins leading a four-way Democratic
primary against Koch, Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin and real estate
developer Richard Ravitch. In the runoff poll, Dinkins would beat
Koch, 58 percent to 32 percent; and Goldin, 54 percent to 26 percent.
   Asked how they would vote in the November general election,
respondents chose Republican Giuliani, the popular former prosecutor
who has not announced his candidacy but has indicated an interest in
running, over Koch or Dinkins.
   Giuliani beat either Koch or Dinkins one-on-one, and both in a
three-way general election. Voters preferred Giuliani to Koch, 58
percent to 31 percent, and to Dinkins, 48 percent to 41 percent.
   The only declared Republican candidate, Former Ambassador Ronald
Lauder, son of cosmetics tycoon Estee Lauder, was not included in
the poll.
   In every ethnic division except Hispanics, Koch met with more
disapproval than approval. Koch, asked to respond, said, ``there's
nothing surprising in the poll.''
   Giuliani saw the numbers as ``encouraging, and they're a
reflection of support I've been getting when I walk along the
streets.''
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 6 percent. No
Democrat candidate got the 40 percent needed to avert a runoff
between the top two candidates. Dinkins had 37 percent, Koch 28
percent, and Ravitch 4 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890312-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     03-12 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Revival of `Measure for Measure' Opens at Lincoln Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Measure for Measure,'' the darkest of
Shakespeare's comedies, deals with sexual hypocrisy, political
intrigue and urban lawlessness.
   In other words, a perfect play for our times, a fact reinforced
by the clear, concise, modern-dress production that opened last week
at the Mitzi Newhouse Theater in Lincoln Center.
   The director is Mark Lamos, artistic head of the Hartford Stage
Company. Lamos built his regional theater reputation in Connecticut
on a series of dazzling interpretations of Shakespeare including a
debonair, 1930-ish ``Twelfth Night,'' a surrealistic and
phantasmagorical ``Pericles'' and a lavish ``Hamlet,'' starring
Richard Thomas. The latter looked like a series of staged photo
opportunities for the evening news.
   His ``Measure for Measure'' is more austere, almost antiseptic in
design and execution. Designer John Conklin's minimalist environment
consists of a white, graffiti-covered wall, a naked light bulb
hanging over the stage and a few pieces of what looks like
secondhand office furniture.
   A sense of dislocation prevails. Although the setting is Vienna,
it could be anywhere. An actor reads a German-language newspaper,
but the graffiti on the wall is in English. The costumes, also by
Conklin, are a mixture of Madison Avenue conservative and Soho chic.
   For a comedy, ``Measure for Measure'' mostly stays somber until
the end of the evening. Until then, audiences have to deal with the
machinations of the Duke who leaves his kingdom in the hands of
Angelo, a self-righteous bureaucrat.
   When Angelo orders Claudio to be executed for his sexual
escapades, he doesn't realize he will fall in love with the
condemned man's sister Isabella. Angelo offers a reprieve in
exchange for sexual favors from the woman. It takes the Duke,
disguised as a friar, quite a while to straighten out the mess.
   Len Cariou's paternal portrayal of the Duke is fine, but his
speaking voice is odd, slow and measured as if he were reciting a
foreign language lesson. Campbell Scott, looking like a young, eager
Wall Street lawyer, projects the coldness of the ambitious Angelo as
well as his frantic desire when the man realizes that he wants
Isabella. Bradley Whitford projects the passion of a young man
afraid to die.
   A sweet-faced Kate Burton makes a forthright heroine,
particularly when she is standing up to Angelo's lechery. She's also
beguiling as she gradually realizes she is falling in love with the
Duke. Their embrace at the end of the play is a triumph of the
romantic spirit that, until then, has been overshadowed by lust.
   Lamos minimizes the comic characters here, but there are some
expert comic cameos by Lois Smith as a blowzy, aging prostitute and
Jack Weston as Pompey, that experienced bawd turned apprentice
executioner. Weston seems as comfortable and proficient with
Shakespeare as he does with television sitcom, a remarkable
accomplishment.
   Several of the minor characters are at odds with Lamos' unfussy
direction particularly Reggie Montgomery as an overly mannered pimp
and Thomas Ikeda as a grating, one-note policeman.
   ``Measure for Measure'' always has been called one of
Shakespeare's problem plays because of its juxiposition of comedy
and tragedy. Both are very near the surface of this dissection of
sexual and governmental power. It's to the credit of the director
and his fine cast that the right balance has been found between the
two.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
