<SECOND>AM-Ailing Mafiosi,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Official Says Mafia Bosses Abuse Hospital Stays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's leading anti-Mafia crusader wants authorities
to tighten up policy on granting hospital stays to jailed mob bosses
who have been hospitalized up to two years, news reports said Sunday.
   Domenico Sica, the high commissioner against organized crime,
sent a letter to Sicilian magistrates urging vigilance when
considering such requests from convicted Mafia members, state radio
and newspapers said.
   La Stampa newspaper reported at least 14 convicted members of the
Mafia, the Sicilian organized crime group, are hospitalized in
Palermo.
   La Repubblica newspaper reported Sica as writing that some Mafia
``heads of clans'' have been in the hospital for two years while the
average hospital stay for inmates is two weeks.
   ``We maintain that there is something wrong with the mechanism of
admissions and diagnosis and it should be remedied as quickly as
possible,'' he was quoted as saying. He said many of the medical
tests could be done in jail.
   In November, the head of Palermo's paramilitary police force
complained that too many of his officers were taken off other duties
to guard convicted hospital patients.
   Sica was quoted as saying at least 100 police officers are needed
to keep Mafia members apart from each other in the hospital and
prevent them from conducting business.
   

