<FIRST>r a AM-LawyerCharges     03-12 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lawyer Charges,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Accuses DA Of Set-up In Order To Get Him To Betry Clients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTROSE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer has accused a district attorney
of making him a target of an undercover operation to coerce him into
working against his own clients, in a case his supporters say could
endanger attorney-client relations.
   Robin Auld, 43, who faces criminal charges in connection with the
case, has filed notice he plans to sue 6th Judicial District
Attorney Victor Reichman. Auld contends Reichman set up the
undercover operation with the intent of trapping Auld and forcing
him to betray his own clients.
   Auld's lawyer, Hal Haddon, says the case threatens the country's
adversarial system of justice ``because a defendant has to be able
to believe his own lawyer isn't working for the DA.''
   He was charged last month with theft by receiving and of
possession a dangerous weapon. He said it was because he had
rejected Reichman's threats. He faces trial May 22 in Durango and
could get up to eight years in prison and lose his law license if
convicted.
   Reichman has declined to comment on the case against Auld, which
he has turned over to a special prosecutor from another district,
Keith Cross of Glenwood Springs.
   According to Auld's complaint, local law enforcement officials
assigned a deputy sheriff, Brent Pace, to pose as a criminal
defendant named ``Colton Young'' and approach Auld for legal help. A
false charge and phony affidavit were filed in court to make it
appear that ``Young'' really was in legal trouble.
   The officials supplied Pace with $500 in public money to pay half
of Auld's fee, the complaint said. After Auld won dismissal of the
misdemeanor charges against Pace, Pace offered to pay the remaining
$500 in legal fees in drugs, and when Auld refused, Pace offered him
guns.
   Auld said he eventually agreed to keep an Uzi machine gun as
collateral on the balance Pace owed, and he was immediately
arrested. He contends Reichman and Police Sergeant John Ball offered
him a deal in which no charges would be filed if Auld agreed to
``set up'' three of his clients for Reichman. Auld refused and
Reichman filed the weapons charges, the complaint said.
   Cross, the special prosecutor, would not comment on the case. But
in a preliminary hearing, he said that Auld believed the gun Pace
had given him was stolen because that's what Pace had said. He also
said Auld knew the weapon had been altered to make it an illegal,
automatic weapon, which Auld disputes.
   Two lawyers were among 15 people, several of them locally
prominent, who signed a public letter questioning Reichman's
treatment of Auld. Attorney Sam Maynes, one of the signers, said the
case ``goes to the very basis of the attorney-client relationship.
It's just not right and that's why I signed the letter.''
   Auld's lawyer, Hal Haddon, made a similar point, saying: ``What
stinks to me is setting up the defense bar and turning them against
their own clients. It destroys people's faith. You'd wonder if your
lawyer is working for the police.''
   Auld's notice of intent to sue, filed Feb. 14, said he will seek
at least $1 million, plus punitive damages, for damage to his
reputation, cost of his defense and loss of earning capacity. Named
along with Reichman are the sheriff and police department in
Durango, the city council, county commission and the Colorado
Department of Public Safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
