<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0676 03-12 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Guerrillas Killed in Lebanon, PLO Group Issues Claim</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with with soldiers sealing home of stabbing
victim, Arafat willing to go to Jerusalem, other developments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers on Sunday killed two
Palestinian guerrillas who entered Israel's self-declared security
zone in south Lebanon on a mission to infiltrate the Jewish state.
   The incident was likely to increase Israeli demands that the
United States halt its dialogue with the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   In the occupied West Bank, a Palestinian stabbed an Israeli
soldier in Bethlehem, and soldiers broke up a funeral for a
17-year-old Palestinian who died Sunday of wounds suffered in a
clash the previous day.
   The soldier was reported in fair condition and Israel radio said
his attacker was captured after being shot three times with rubber
bullets.
   Radio reports said the soldier was stabbed with a kitchen knife
as troops ordered youths to erase anti-Israeli graffiti and take
down outlawed Palestinian flags.
   The West Bank man who died was identified as Mohammed Shrain of
the Aida refugee camp. Witnesses said soldiers blocked off the camp
and fired tear gas and rubber bullets to block his funeral. The army
confirmed the death and said it placed a curfew on the camp.
   At least 395 Palestinians and 17 Israelis been killed during the
15-month uprising against Israel's occupation of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   In the occupied West Bank, the army sealed with concrete the home
of a Palestinian who stabbed an Israeli soldier Sunday in the
biblical city of Bethlehem, Arab and Israeli news reports said.
   An army spokesman said the alleged assailant was caught and
confessed to the stabbing. The sealing or demolition of homes is
routine punishment for suspects in such attacks. Israel views the
punishment as a deterrent to future perpetrators.
   At least 12 Palestinians were reported wounded Sunday in clashes
with soldiers throughout the occupied territories.
   The army confirmed eight of the injuries.
   The fighting in south Lebanon erupted when two armed guerrillas
were spotted on the edge of the Israeli security zone near Hasbaya,
about five miles north of Israel's border.
   No Israeli troops were injured, Israeli military officials said.
   The radical Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command, in a statement issued at Rashaya, Lebanon, said the
guerrillas were among a group sent on a military operation into
Israel. The others escaped, said a group spokesman, who insisted on
anonymity.
   The confrontation was the third between PLO guerrillas and
Israeli soldiers in less than three weeks. Israel cited the two
earlier encounters in calling on the United States to call off its
dialogue with the PLO.
   Israel maintains the fighting in the security zone is evidence
that PLO chief Yasser Arafat is violating his pledge to give up
terrorism. Arafat's pledge was behind the U.S. agreement in December
to open a dialogue with the PLO.
   Israel established the six- by 10-mile wide zone in south Lebanon
to protect its northern border when it pulled most of its forces out
of the region in 1985, ending a three-year occupation.
   Arafat, meanwhile, was quoted Sunday as saying he is willing to
go to Jerusalem to convince Israel's leaders to agree to an
international conference on Middle East peace. But he said he would
only do so with the agreement of other Arab states.
   Arafat spoke in an interview with Italy's La Repubblica
newspaper. He has made similar statements in the past.
   Also Sunday, the army said a colonel had been suspended from his
post for allegedly stealing a wristwatch off the body of a dead
guerrilla.
   The colonel was identified only as ``Col. R.,'' and the spokesman
said he was an ``experienced and a veteran fighter.'' He was
suspended from his post pending clarification of the legal
ramifications of the incident, the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
