<FIRST>r a AM-MissionfromLockerbie     03-12 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mission from Lockerbie,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scottish Officials Comfort Grieving Families Of Lockerbie Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Scottish constables arrived Sunday to calm
families who say they can't put to rest loved ones killed by a
terrorist bomb on Pan Am Flight 103 until the victims' personal
belongings are returned to them.
   The senior police officers wanted to ease the pain and confusion
felt by many families of the 259 victims whose possessions have been
withheld during the investigation of the Dec. 21 plane explosion
over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Assistant Chief Constable Paul Newell said he and his fellow
officers also wanted to quell rumors.
   ``We got the feeling there was a great deal of misinformation
about what we were doing with the personal items,'' Newell said.
``We came to tell the relatives the truth right from the horse's
mouth.''
   More than 100 people gathered in Boston to hear the constables'
reassurances that many of the victims' personal belongings would be
returned and to examine maps of the rugged terrain where the
victims' bodies were found.
   ``It's a very traumatic thing for us,'' said Joe Horgan of West
Point, Pa., whose brother-in-law was on Flight 103. ``You run the
gamut of emotions, reliving the whole thing.''
   Horgan said the grieving families ``can't complete the healing
process until those possessions are returned.''
   Matthew Coyle, who lost one of his 20-year-old twin daughters in
the bombing, said he and his wife came from their home in
Wallingford, Conn., to try to make some sense of the tragedy.
   ``It's a step,'' he said. ``I'm not sure where it's taking us but
it's a step.''
   Jeanine Boulanger of Shrewsbury said that because officials had
not recovered her 21-year-old daughter's body, she had pinned all
her hopes on retrieving some of the college student's possessions.
   ``She was an actress, a singer, a dancer and a poet,'' Mrs.
Boulanger said. ``These items, her journal, they're the only
tangible things we have to hold on to.''
   Newell flatly denied rumors that investigators had destroyed
victims' property.
   ``Nothing but nothing could be further from the truth,'' he said.
``But we want to make sure to clarify that for people ... who right
now have nothing.''
   Police have found and catalogued more than 11,000 items strewn
over 40 miles of Scottish countryside. But even though ownership has
been established and the property has been eliminated from the
criminal inquiry, most families are still waiting.
   Newell said the first property was returned in mid-February via
the U.S. Consulate in Edinburgh and that the process was continuing.
   In addition to those on board, 11 residents of Lockerbie were
killed when the wreckage of the Boeing 747 fell to the ground after
an explosion. The plane was en route from London to New York.
   Investigators have traced the bomb to a portable radio packed
with the luggage, but have not yet established what person or group
was responsible.
   The Scottish officers also met over the weekend with about 120
families in New York. They were scheduled to travel to Detroit on
Monday and Canton, Ohio, on Tuesday before returning home.
</TEXT>
