<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-IRA     03-12 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-IRA,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Police Increase Security for Leading Britons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have increased security around leading
figures following reports of an IRA assassination squad at large in
Britain and a list of prominent people found at a bomb-making site
in London, Press Association reported.
   The domestic news agency says police think the Irish Republican
Army unit, identified by Home Secretary Douglas Hurd on Wednesday,
may be working from a list of political and public figures similar
to one found Dec. 21 in a south London IRA bomb factory.
   ``We can confirm that a number of names of people prominent in
public life in Britain were found on a list in the house in Clapham
in December,'' Scotland Yard said Saturday. ``Each individual named
has been given suitable security advice.''
   Scotland Yard did not disclose who was on the list found in
Clapham nor say how many names it contained.
   The discovery of a cache of Semtex explosive and firearms in
woods near the northern coastal resort of Scarborough on Tuesday as
well as 22 pounds of the explosive in a London reservoir led the
Anti-Terrorist Squad to issue the warnings to leading figures, Press
Association said.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and senior Cabinet ministers are
to address a Conservative Party meeting in Scarborough's Crown Hotel
on Friday.
   Scotland Yard never discusses the security of individuals or
reveals details of any armed escorts. Press Association, however,
said it understood that a number of people thought to be on the list
have been given round-the-clock protection.
   The IRA has been waging a violent campaign to drive the British
out of the largely Protestant province of Northern Ireland and unite
it with the predominantly Roman Catholic Republic Ireland.
   On Wednesday, Hurd said a small gang equipped with explosives and
guns was at large in Britain. The government and security services
say the unit might be planning a bombing campaign on the British
mainland.
   The group is thought to have been responsible for the Aug. 1 bomb
blast at army barracks at Mill Hill, north London, which killed one
soldier and injured nine, and another blast at Ternhill, Shrewsbury,
Feb. 20. Only one soldier was injured in that bombing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
