<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Churches     03-12 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Churches,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Clergy Predict Black-White Church Split Will Persist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's main Afrikaner
church is likely to remain estranged from its black and mixed-race
counterparts despite its latest and most explicit repudiation of
apartheid, two dissident white clergymen said Sunday.
   Beyers Naude and Nico Smith, ministers who left the white Dutch
Reformed Church to join its black offspring, wrote newspaper
articles suggesting an irrevocable split was likely because of the
white church leadership's reluctance to support concrete
anti-apartheid action.
   Naude and Smith were assessing a five-day conference they
attended last week, aimed at finding common ground among the church
branches on racial issues.
   During the conference the white church, to which President P.W.
Botha and most of his Cabinet belong, declared apartheid a sin.
   However, delegates from the white church did not endorse a
resolution advocating civil disobedience to oppose apartheid and did
not join in a call for the abolition of specific racial segregation
laws.
   Smith, who broke from the white church in 1982 and now is a
pastor in a black township, wrote in the Sunday Times that the
conference was ``in many ways a dialogue of the deaf.''
   ``Those belonging to the world of the oppressor could not hear or
understand the cries and anger of those living in the world of the
oppressed,'' he wrote. ``The white church was once again exposed as
a captive of the Afrikaner volk (people) and the Nationalist
government.''
   Naude, whose split with the white church dates back to the 1960s,
wrote in the Sunday Star newspaper that ``the already fragile thread
of fellowship may be irrevocably broken'' if whites react
unsympathetically to the strong anti-apartheid resolutions adopted
by the black and mixed-race delegates.
   One area of common ground established at the conference was
opposition to the 33-month-old state of emergency, during which the
government has detained thousands of black activists.
   Leaders of the white, black and mixed-race churches reportedly
plan to make a joint appeal to the government to lift the emergency
and halt detention without trial.
   Sunday was designated by activists across South Africa as
National Detainees Day, and church services were held in several
communities to express solidarity with those held without charge.
</TEXT>
