<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Demonstration     03-12 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Demonstration,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest in Moscow, Leningrad and Latvian Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of pro-democrats demonstrated in Moscow
and Leningrad on Sunday, while thousands of Latvians rallied in
support of a grass-roots political organization, organizers said.
   Police arrested about 100 protesters in the Moscow and Leningrad
protests, one activist said.
   The demonstrators in Moscow, estimated at 1,500, unfurled the
white, blue and red flag of Russia that flew after the February
Revolution in 1917, during the eight months of shaky attempts to
found a democracy before the Bolsheviks took over, the activist said.
   An estimated 200,000 people marched in Riga, the Latvian capital,
to express support for the aims of the Latvian People's Front, which
has come under fire from a Russian nationalist group, one of the
protesters said.
   Boris Sokolov of the People's Front said the protest in the
Latvian capital was the biggest protest ever seen in that Soviet
republic.
   Thousands gathered in a downtown square to counter increasing
pressure on the People's Front from Interfront, a largely Russian
organization that has organized at least one strike to protest
People's Front moves to restore Latvian as the republic's dominant
language, Sokolov said in a telephone interview.
   Some people carried placards calling for Latvian independence and
favoring the language law. Participants agreed to send a message to
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the Latvian parliament favoring
democratization, Sokolov said.
   The rally ended peacefully and no arrests were made, he said.
   The Democratic Union, a fledgling political party in a nation
that bans any alternative to the ruling communists, organized the
Moscow and Leningrad demonstrations. The People's Front, unlike the
Democratic Union, claims broad-based support and has worked with the
Communist Party and local authorities to pursue its reform program.
   The Leningrad protest, against allegedly undemocratic sections in
a new election law, drew 7,000 people and 1,500 police and crowd
control officers, said Yuri Mityunov of the Democratic Union in
Moscow. He said authorities detained 65 people.
   About 1,500 people attended the demonstration on Moscow's
Mayakovsky Square and 40 people were detained, he said. It was not
clear if charges would be filed.
   In the Volga River city of Kuibyshev, 300 people marched 2 miles
down city streets Sunday to mark the anniversary of the February
revolution, and 100 of them continued the meeting in a factory hall,
Mityunov said.
   They carried placards with such slogans as, ``Political
opposition is the guarantee of democracy.''
   The Kuibyshev protest proceeded unhindered after the organizers
threatened a group hunger strike and Western media coverage of any
repressive measures, Mityunov said.
</TEXT>
