<FIRST>r a AM-Navajos-MacDonald     03-12 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navajos-MacDonald,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>MacDonald Forces Dissidents Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Embattled Navajo Chairman Peter
MacDonald ordered two tribal officials fired and locks on two
buildings changed, prompting a predecessor to say Sunday that the
move represented ``a police state.''
   MacDonald has been under fire since witnesses, including his son,
told a U.S. Senate select committee last month that he had taken
kickbacks and bribes from companies wanting to do business with the
nation's largest Indian tribe.
   The latest developments came after a meeting Friday by 44
dissident members of the 88-member Tribal Council. The dissidents
elected an interim chairman and vice chairman and placed Vice
Chairman Johnny R. Thompson on administrative leave.
   That same day, MacDonald's staff was ordered to fire James
Henderson, director of the legislative affairs office, and Henderson
aide Larry Foster, said Alyce Rouwalk, assistant area director for
the Navajo office of the federal Bureau of Indian Affairs.
   MacDonald has accused Henderson and Foster of siding with the
dissidents.
   Late Friday, tribal police were ordered to change the locks on
the council building and the legislative office, said Ms. Rouwalk.
   Former Tribal Chairman Peterson Zah said in an interview Sunday
on Phoenix radio station KFYI that MacDonald's move was uncalled for
and represented another case of ``excessive use of police force on
this reservation.''
   ``So in essence, the bottom line is we really have a police state
here,'' Zah said.
   Following the Senate committee hearings, the council voted Feb.
17 to place MacDonald on leave, but he has maintained he is still in
charge.
   MacDonald spokeswoman Pazbah McCullah said Saturday the chairman
had no comment on Friday's events. No one could be reached for
comment Sunday because tribal offices were closed.
   Approximately 150,000 of the Navajos' 200,000 members live on the
reservation, which includes much of northeastern Arizona as well as
parts of northwestern New Mexico and southeastern Utah.
