<HEAD>Actor-Stuntman Skeeter Vaughan Dead At 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEQUIM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Skeeter Vaughan, a Cherokee Inidian whose
knife-throwing and tomahawk skills led him to a career as actor and
stuntman in movies and television, has died of a heart attack at age
66.
   Vaughan died Wednesday while dining with friends in nearby Port
Angeles, said his daughter, Cherokee Vaughan Dykes.
   Vaughan appeared in more than 100 movies, television shows and
commercials. His film credits included ``The Last of the Mohicans,''
``Revolution,'' and ``The Great White Hope.'' His TV work included
``Magnum P.I.,'' ``Gunsmoke'' and ``The Six Million Dollar Man.''
   Vaughan was also a charter member of the Hollywood Stuntmen's
Hall of Fame, said Mrs. Dykes.
   Vaughan, whose Indian name was Grey Otter, was born on a
reservation in California and grew up near Pendleton, Ore. He began
his show business career at age 12 in a traveling medicine show as a
knife and tomahawk thrower.
   In addition to Mrs. Dykes, he is survived by two other daughters,
a son and two granddaughters.
