<FIRST>u i AM-India-Tibet     03-12 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Tibet,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetans Protest Chinese Rule in Their Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police wielding bamboo canes pushed back
Tibetan women who tried to march to Parliament Sunday to protest
Chinese rule and violence in their homeland.
   About 20 women sustained scrapes and scratches, either from the
police officers' bamboo canes or from falling on the gravel when
they tried to push through a metal barricade. Parliament was not in
session at the time.
   Clashes between Tibetan demonstrators and Chinese police last
week in Lhasa, Tibet's capital, left 16 people dead and more than
100 wounded by China's official count. Western travelers said the
death toll was higher and could be 20 or 30.
   The killings occurred during protests that began a few days
before the anniversary of the March 10, 1959 uprising in Tibet that
was quashed by China.
   Sunday's demonstration in New Delhi was timed to coincide with
the 30th anniversary of the day thousands of Tibetan women staged
freedom marches in Lhasa as men stayed indoors out of fear for their
safety.
   On March 17, 1959, the Tibetans' spiritual and temporal leader,
the Dalai Lama, fled across the Himalayas to India, where he remains
in exile with about 100,000 other Tibetans.
   After New Delhi police thwarted Sunday's march about a mile from
Parliament, about 200 women staged a peaceful protest beside India
Gate, the huge stone arch honoring Indian soldiers who died in the
service of their British colonial rulers.
   As they chanted slogans calling for an end to Chinese rule, at
least a half-dozen of the women fainted in the midday sun and were
carried to shade trees by young women wearing T-shirts that read
``Free Tibet'' and ``Stop Repression in Tibet.''
   The Dalai Lama, revered by Tibetan Buddhists as their god-king,
has said he would accept Chinese control of military and foreign
policy in Tibet in exchange for greater autnomy.
   Tibetans say their homeland was independent before the Chinese
invasion in 1949, but China maintains it had been an integral part
of China for centuries.
</TEXT>
