<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-PlanesDown     03-12 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Planes Down,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Called Off for American Pilot Who Ditched Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers on Sunday called off their
search for a Minnesota pilot who ditched his small plane in the
frigid Atlantic Ocean four days ago.
   Todd Michaelson, 29, of Minneapolis, was the lone occupant of the
single-engine Piper Saratoga. He reported engine troubles Wednesday
afternoon and went down a short time later.
   ``The search has been reduced which means resources have been
stood down,'' said Maj. Phil MacMillan of the Halifax Search and
rescue centre. ``A general marine broadcast has gone out to all
shipping in the area to keep an eye out.''
   Two British and one Canadian patrol plane and a Canadian research
vessel continued to search an area about 900 miles northeast of
Newfoundland until darkness fell Sunday.
   Michaelson, who was delivering the plane to Ireland for Orient
Air International of Minneapolis, had a life raft and survival suit
with him. A flare thought to have been fired by him was spotted late
Wednesday night and searchers later found some debris believed to be
from his plane.
   Search officials on Friday stopped hunting for a second small
plane that ditched in the same area as Michaelson's Thursday
morning. The pilot, an American in his 40s, was not identified.
</TEXT>
