<DOCNO> AP890312-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-SutherlandRecital     03-12 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sutherland Recital,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dame Joan Sutherland Sings Solo at Met</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dame Joan Sutherland, opera's most famous
coloratura soprano, who made her Metropolitan Opera debut in ``Lucia
di Lammermoor'' in 1961 to great acclaim, sang her first solo
recital at the Met on Sunday and again deserved the acclaim she
received.
   Her husband, conductor Richard Bonynge, was her deferential piano
accompanist.
   Dame Joan has spent most of her career in the bel canto opera
repertoire, singing soprano parts written to show off the sound of
the voice, its beauty, flexibility and accuracy, with much less
emphasis on the words.
   She chose that type of song and aria for her recital. She's still
a singer well worth hearing, who can be greatly enjoyed and
appreciated.
   For the most part, she didn't choose flamboyant selections and
she only chose two that are generally familiar. Those were Balfe's
``I dreamt I dwelt in marble halls'' and Offenbach's ``O mon cher
amant'' from ``La Perichole.''
   Many of the songs were extravagantly melancholy, like the first,
``Sad Likeness of my Phyllis'' by Bellini, with its line ``I have
shed bitter tears over your ashes.''
   Her one encore was ``There's No Place Like Home.'' As she sang
it, Dame Joan glanced up and around the opera house. The Met isn't
``ever so humble'' but it has been one of her special homes, where
she is always happily greeted, for almost three decades.
   It's interesting that even a simple tune like ``There's No Place
like Home'' sounds like an aria when Dame Joan sings it. Several of
the other songs in the recital were combinations of folk and art
songs. They sounded, sung by this singer, like classical art songs.
   Dame Joan didn't use her first two or three songs to loosen her
vocal chords. She sounded fine from the beginning. Her ``silver
flute'' voice has become a bit darker but not much; the difference
is heard more in added warmth. Her accuracy is phenomenal. She sang
perfect trills in some of the brief coloratura passages. The two
selections on the program with the most exciting coloratura were
Ricci's 1850 ``Io non sono piu l'Annetta'' and Massenet's 1888
``Autumn Thoughts.'' We particularly enjoyed Tosti's flowingly
melodic ``La serenata'' and the six Massenet songs.
   Other composers heard were Meyerbeer, Rossini, Donizetti, David,
Bizet, Chaminade, Godard and Gounod.
   Sometimes Dame Joan's tone sounds a bit hollow and sometimes she
scoops up to notes, which isn't new. But her tone is beautiful; she
isn't shrill or harsh.
   The capacity audience jumped up to award the singer a standing
ovation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
