<FIRST>r f AM-GAFTrial     03-12 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Trial,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Second Day in Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the GAF Corp. stock manipulation
trial asked Sunday to review all charts, graphs and closing
arguments in its second day of deliberations in the Wall Street
fraud case.
   The panel is deciding whether GAF and its vice chairman, James T.
Sherwin, tried to illegally boost the share price of Union Carbide
Corp. in 1986 prior to the sale of a large block of the stock.
   The case is the first to reach the trial phase in a series of
prosecutions by the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office emanating from
Wall Street's insider trading scandals.
   GAF, two subsidiaries and Sherwin were indicted last July on
charges of stock manipulation, securities fraud, wire fraud and
conspiracy. The company faces up to $12 million in fines while
Sherwin could be sentenced to up to 40 years in jail and fined $2
million.
   After a six-week re-trial, the jury received the case from U.S.
District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe and began deliberating Saturday,
when it re-heard testimony by the government's star witness, Los
Angeles broker Boyd L. Jefferies.
   The jury's request Sunday was viewed as a sign that it was not
pinning its decision on the credibility of Jefferies' testimony.
Jefferies said Sherwin asked him to raise Union Carbide stock to $22
a share or higher in October 1986.
   GAF sold 5 million shares of the stock in mid-November 1986. The
Wayne, N.J.-based chemicals manufacturer failed earlier that year in
a takeover bid for Carbide.
   Jefferies testified as part of a plea bargain with the government
after agreeing to plead guilty to two criminal securities law
violations in connection with his dealings with jailed arbitrager
Ivan Boesky.
   Jefferies is expected to testify in two key securities fraud
cases later this year.
</TEXT>
