<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing-Health     03-12 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Health,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Health Study Set For Boeing Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. officials and the union representing
Boeing production workers have authorized a new study of work
conditions at the company's Auburn plant, where dozens of employees
say they've fallen ill from working with chemicals.
   Company and union officials on Friday confirmed the new study.
   Last year, dozens of Auburn plant employees who worked with
phenolic resins complained of illnesses ranging from headaches and
nausea to memory loss. Twenty workers filed insurance claims.
   The illnesses were the subject of congressional hearings two
weeks ago in Washington, D.C.
   State and federal inspectors found the plant to be in compliance
with safety standards, but Boeing still halted use of the resins,
used to make plastic parts for aircraft interiors.
   ``We're not convinced nor do we know that's the only problem,''
said Tom Baker, president of District 751 of the International
Association of Machinists &amp; Aerospace workers, which represents
40,000 Boeing workers.
   Baker said questions still linger about whether low-level
exposure to the resins might cause health problems, even if chemical
levels in the air are within government limits.
   A committee of six company and union executives decided to
proceed with the new study recommended by occupational health
experts from the University of Washington and the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
   Dr. Alan Ducatman, director of environmental medical services at
MIT, said he recommended an extensive study because nothing less
would properly test some theories as to why the workers were getting
sick. He declined to outline those theories.
   Boeing spokesman Paul Binder declined to discuss details of the
study, saying they have not been settled.
</TEXT>
