<FIRST>r f AM-FuturesMeeting     03-12 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Futures Meeting,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Industry Leaders To Meet Under Cloud Of Federal Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the futures industry will meet this
week in Boca Raton, Fla., the traditional sunny setting for their
annual gathering. But it will be clouded this year by a federal
investigation of trading fraud at the world's two largest futures
exchanges.
   Nearly two months have elapsed since the FBI ``sting'' operation
at the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
was disclosed. No indictments have been issued and the story has
been replaced on the financial pages by fresher controversies.
   Yet the scandal remains a major concern among the 1,100 brokerage
executives, money managers and exchange officers registered for the
Futures Industry Association's meeting, and talk of it is likely to
surface frequently in both private conversations and public
discussions during the three-day affair.
   ``People are calling me every day and asking `What's going on
with this thing?''' said John Damgard, president of the
Washington-based trade group. ``Hardly a day goes by that we don't
talk about what effect the investigation and the allegations are
going to have on the program.''
   But only the Justice Department knows for sure where the probe is
headed, and it's not talking.
   What is known is that hundreds of grand-jury subpoenas have been
issued, many of them to futures traders who have been questioned
about the opportunities for cheating customers while executing their
orders in the boisterous futures pits.
   Damgard said the government's investigation did not play a major
role in shaping the FIA meeting program. But neither has the
association shied away from scheduling sessions in which
probe-related issues are bound to arise.
   Thursday's conference-opening panel discussion on self-regulation
and trading practices may further illuminate the Chicago exchanges'
responses to the criticism that has buffeted the industry since the
investigation was revealed. Board of Trade Chairman Karsten ``Cash''
Mahlmann and Chicago Merc President William Brodsky will be among
the panelists.
   ``I think you will find the possibility that a guy like Cash
Mahlmann might discuss some of the changes the Board of Trade has
announced,'' said Robert Wilmouth, who will moderate the session and
who is himself president of the National Futures Association, a
congressionally mandated self-regulatory organization.
   The Board of Trade is planning a $1 million upgrade of its
computerized trade-surveillance system, which federal regulators
recently criticized as inadequate for detecting abuses, and both
Chicago exchanges are reviewing their trading rules.
   Futures are contracts to buy or sell a commodity or financial
instrument for a specified price at a future date.
   The FIA meeting also will include a speech Thursday by Wendy
Gramm, chairman of the federal Commodity Futures Trading Commission,
which regulates futures trading. And it will give many in the
industry their first look at the Chicago Board of Trade's planned
off-hours electronic trading system.
   The investigation in Chicago is hastening the move toward
electronic trading, which will permit around-the-clock trading of
futures contracts and, some contend, provide a better audit trail
than traditional open-outcry trading.
   The Board of Trade revealed last month that it was working on an
electronic trading system to compete with Globex, a similar system
being developed by the Chicago Merc and London-based Reuters
Holdings PLC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890312-0089 </DOCNO>
