<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     03-12 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens, Stock Prices Lower In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar strengthened against the Japanese
yen Monday, while stock prices declined slightly.
   The dollar opened at 129.38 yen, up 0.50 yen from Friday's close
of 128.88 yen.
   Dealers said the U.S. currency's strength followed a similar
trend in New York on Friday, when the U.S. Labor Department reported
a continuing strong growth in domestic employment.
   However, the report that the U.S. unemployment rate fell to a
15-year low of 5.1 percent in February, from 5.4 percent the
previous month, created concerns that the U.S. central bank may
raise interest rates to cool down the economy in an ever-tightening
labor market.
   Higher interest rates tend to make the dollar more attractive to
foreign investors.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 45.33-point gainer Friday, shed 48.54 points or
0.15 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 31,653.24.
</TEXT>
