<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Women'sEarnings     03-12 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Women's Earnings,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Black Women Outpacing White Women In Drive For Equal Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educational and career advances by black
women, combined with a lull in the earning power of black men, have
narrowed the salary gap between the two, a University of Michigan
researcher says.
   By contrast, white women are lagging in their attempt to close
the wage gap with their male counterparts, said Reynolds Farley, a
research associate with the school's Population Studies Center.
   ``This improvement in the earnings of black women compared with
those of black men is the result of greater educational attainment,
more occupational opportunities for black women and a virtual
stagnation of the earnings of black men in the last 15 years,''
Farley said last week.
   In 1986, he said, black women ages 25 to 54 earned an average of
$12,100 a year, or about 75 percent of the average black male's
yearly salary of $16,000. White women in the same age bracket
averaged $12,800, roughly half the average white male's annual pay.
   ``Compared with the incomes of most black men, the average black
woman's income has risen sharply since World War II,'' Farley said,
noting that in 1947, black women earned only 34 percent of a black
man's average salary.
   Farley conducted the study with Suzanne M. Bianchi, a demographer
at the U.S. Bureau of the Census' Center for Demographic Studies.
</TEXT>
