<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PittstonDebate     03-12 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pittston Debate,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston, Mine Union Agree To Public Debate In Labor Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials of The Pittson Co. and the
United Mine Workers have agreed to publicly debate issues in a
contract dispute that has left coal miners in three Appalachian
states without a contract for more than a year.
   The Greenwich Fellowship of Clergy suggested the rare public
forum after a demonstration by coal miners outside Pittston
headquarters in Greenwich last month, and invited Pittston Chairman
Paul W. Douglas and Mine Workers President Richard Trumka to
participate.
   In separate letters Friday to the Rev. C. Edward Deyton, pastor
of Diamond Hill United Methodist Church in Greenwich and fellowship
chairman, Trumka accepted the offer and Douglas designated Gene
Matthis, chairman of the Pittston Coal Group in Lebanon, Va., as the
company's representative at the debate.
   No date has been set for the forum in Greenwich. Both Douglas and
Trumka said they hope it can be scheduled soon.
   In their original letters to Douglas and Trumka, the clergy
expressed hope that ``an evening of discussion ... would help bring
about a healthy reconciliation.''
   Members of the United Mine Workers have been working for more
than a year without a contract in Virginia, Kentucky and West
Virginia.
   Pittson, a diversified company that also is involved in air
freight and security systems, employs about 1,700 people in 20
mines. It has laid off about 4,000 miners in recent years due to
technological advances and the closing of mines.
   Miners threatened to strike Feb. 1, one year after agreeing to
work without a contract while negotiations continued, but accepted a
30- to 60-day cooling off period requested by the governors of the
three states.
   Pittston spokesman William J. Byrne Jr. was skeptical at first
about the forum, saying last week, ``I certainly have a hard time
understanding how Greenwich can be helpful in Appalachia.''
   Greenwich is one of Connecticut's most affluent communities,
located near New York City.
   Trumka said in his statement that the clergy had ``earned out
respect and appreciation'' for sponsoring the forum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
